{[#]} 6. Be3 e5 7. d5 Na6 8. g4 Nc5 9. Bf3 {[%csl Re1,Rf3,Rg4] A somewhat
artificial setup, but White counts on the position remaining closed. In this
game, Black demonstrates a strong counter-idea.} c6 $1 10. b4 cxd5 {An
important intermezzo.} 11. cxd5 {[#]} (11. bxc5 d4) 11... Ncxe4 $3 {A piece
sacrifice to open up the center while white pieces are undeveloped.} ({also
nothing wrong with} 11... Ncd7 $5) 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 f5 14. gxf5 gxf5 15.
Bc2 f4 16. Bd2 $2 {Materialistic and passive.} ({White should have fought with
the initiative with a counter-sacrifice:} 16. Qh5 e4 $1 17. Bxe4 h6 (17... Rf7
$5 18. Rc1 fxe3 19. Nf3 exf2+ 20. Kxf2 $13) 18. Qg6 Qf6 19. Qh7+ Kf7 20. Rc1
fxe3 21. fxe3 Bd7 $13) 16... e4 $1 {[%csl Re1,Yg7] opening the files and
diagonals.} 17. Bxe4 (17. Rc1 {[#]} Qh4 $1 {The right way to continue the
attack!} (17... e3 $2 18. Qh5 $1 exd2+ 19. Kxd2 $132) 18. Bxe4 Re8 19. Qe2 Bg4
20. Nf3 Qh5 $19) 17... Qe7 18. f3 Bf5 {White loses material now.} 19. Rc1 Bxe4
20. Qe2 Qh4+ 21. Qf2 Qxf2+ 22. Kxf2 Bd4+ 23. Kg2 Bxd5 $19 24. Ne2 Bb6 25. a4
Rf7 26. Bxf4 Re8 27. Nc3 Bc6 28. b5 Rxf4 29. bxc6 bxc6 30. Kg3 Ref8 31. Rhf1
Be3 32. Rc2 Rc4 33. Re1 Bf4+ 34. Kg2 d5 35. Ree2 Rf6 36. Nd1 Rg6+ 37. Kf1 Rxa4
0-1

