{[#]} 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 a6 9. Be2 b6 10. Qd2 Bb7 11. f3 Nbd7 12. O-O-O {
Queenside castling leads to double-edged positions with mutual chances.} Ne5
13. Kb1 Rc8 14. b3 {[%csl Rb1] White king is more exposed now as the a1-h8
diagonal is free of pawns.} e6 15. g4 Qe7 16. h4 {[%csl Rg4] [#] Necessary,
but also weakens the g4 square.} b5 $1 {The most ambitious move - opening the
c-file for attack and clearing the long diagonal for the attack.} (16... Nexg4
$5 17. fxg4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4+ 19. Bd3 Bxh1 20. Rxh1 Qb7 21. Rh3 d5 22. h5 $13
) (16... Rfd8 $5 17. h5 d5 $13) 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Ndxb5 Nexg4 19. fxg4 $2 ({
The diagonal should have been shut with} 19. Bd4 Ne5 20. Bxe5 dxe5 $13) 19...
Bxe4+ $2 ({Black could have cleared the long diagonal with} 19... Rxc3 $3 20.
Qxc3 ({or} 20. Nxc3 Nxe4 21. Nxe4 Bxe4+ 22. Bd3 Qf6 {[%csl Rb1]} 23. Bxe4 Qa1+
24. Kc2 Qxa2+ 25. Kd3 Qa6+ 26. Kc2 Rc8+) 20... Bxe4+ $1 (20... Nxe4 $2 21. Qb4)
21. Bd3 Bxh1 22. Rxh1 Nd5 23. Qd2 Nxe3 24. Qxe3 Qf6 $19) ({In case of} 19...
Nxe4 $2 20. Nxe4 Bxe4+ 21. Bd3 Qf6 {White has} 22. Bd4) 20. Bd3 $2 (20. Nxe4 {
looks scary for White, but it is not so bad since after} Nxe4 21. Qe1 $16 {
Black does not have a direct way toward the king.} Qf6 22. Bd4 $18) 20... Bxh1
21. Rxh1 Nxg4 22. Bg5 Qb7 23. Rg1 Ne5 $17 {In a complicated position, Black
has the upper hand as his king is safer.} 24. Rc1 (24. Nxd6 Qb6) 24... Nxd3 25.
Qxd3 Qa6 26. a4 d5 27. h5 h6 28. Be3 g5 29. Bd4 e5 30. Bf2 Rfd8 31. Qf5 d4 32.
Ne4 Rxc1+ 33. Kxc1 Qc6+ 34. Kd2 Qd5 35. Nf6+ Bxf6 36. Qxf6 Rc8 37. Qa6 Qc5 38.
Ke2 Qc2+ 39. Kf3 Qd3+ 40. Kg2 Qe4+ 41. Kg3 Rc2 42. Qf6 Qh4+ 43. Kg2 Qg4+ 44.
Kh2 Qxh5+ 45. Kg3 Qh4+ 46. Kg2 Qg4+ 47. Kh2 Qf4+ 48. Qxf4 gxf4 49. Kg1 Rc1+ 0-1

