{[#]} 7... exd5 8. exd5 a6 9. a4 {White prevents b5.} a5 $146 {A novelty, but
it seems to be an inaccuracy, because White can place his N on e2.} ({In a
previous game Black played} 9... d6 10. Nf3 (10. Nge2 Nbd7 $1 $13) 10... Re8+
11. Be3 a5 12. O-O Na6 13. Rc1 Nb4 14. Bb1 Bd7 15. Re1 Re7 16. Qd2 Qf8 $1 17.
Bg5 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 h6 19. Bf4 $14 {1/2 (38) Rodshtein,M (2678) -Ivanisevic,I 
(2623) St Petersburg RUS 2014}) 10. Nge2 {White has a very pleasant position
with an advantage in space.} Na6 11. Bg5 Nb4 12. Bb1 b6 $1 {Black wants to
attack the c4 P to provoke b3 so as to weaken the long diagonal.} 13. O-O Ba6
14. Nb5 $1 (14. b3 h6 $15) 14... h6 {[#]} 15. Bc1 $1 {I like this move. At the
first sight, it's more active to move the B to h4, but after this move, White
has a strong plan of kingside attack in mind with the two bishops.} (15. Bh4
Bxb5 16. axb5 Qc7 {Black seems fine.}) 15... Bxb5 16. axb5 Ne8 {[#]} 17. Ra3 $1
{The key attacking idea. Black kingside has been softened up, so the rook
moves to g3 to prepare a sacrifice on g6.} Nd6 18. Rg3 Nxc4 $2 (18... Re8 19.
Bxg6 $1 fxg6 20. Rxg6 $36) 19. Nf4 $36 {There is no defence against the
onslaught on the kingside.} Ne5 20. Nh5 Qh4 21. Nxg7 Kxg7 22. Re1 d6 23. Re4
Qd8 24. Qh5 1-0

