{[#]} 7. g4 e5 8. d5 Nc5 9. f3 a5 ({The other plan is} 9... Ne8 10. Qd2 f5 11.
exf5 $1 {Precise. White wants to open the g-file, but at the right moment.} (
11. gxf5 gxf5 12. O-O-O Qh4 13. Bg5 Qh5) 11... gxf5 12. O-O-O a6 (12... f4 13.
Bxc5 dxc5 14. Bd3) (12... Qh4 13. Bg5 {[%cal Rh4h5]}) 13. gxf5 $1 Bxf5 14. h4
b5 {[#]} 15. h5 (15. Nh3 $5 Kh8 (15... b4 16. Ne4) 16. Ng5) (15. b4 Nd7 16.
cxb5 a5 17. bxa5 Rxa5) (15. cxb5 axb5 16. Bxb5 Nb3+ 17. axb3 Ra1+ 18. Nb1 Rxb1#
) 15... b4 16. Ne4 $1 {This pawn sacrifice leads to a strong kingside attack.}
Nxe4 (16... b3 17. a3 Nxe4 18. fxe4 Bxe4 19. Bg2 Bc2 20. h6 Bf6 21. Rf1 e4 22.
Ne2) 17. fxe4 Bxe4 18. Bg2 Bxg2 (18... Bf5 19. Ne2 Kh8 20. Ng3 Bg4 21. Rdg1)
19. Qxg2 Kh8 20. h6 Bf6 21. Nh3 {Black king is exposed as White employs his
rooks on the open files.} Qd7 22. Rhg1 Qa4 23. Rdf1 b3 24. axb3 Qxb3 25. Rxf6
Qxe3+ 26. Kc2 {1-0 (26) Lupulescu,C (2634)-Eminov,O (2274) Konya 2017 CBM 179
Extra [dkulj]}) 10. Qd2 c6 11. Nge2 cxd5 12. cxd5 Bd7 13. Ng3 {This is a very
potent attacking setup for White.} a4 $6 {Too slow.} ({Black should have
countered the kingside attack with} 13... Rc8 14. h4 h5 $1 15. gxh5 Nxh5 16.
Nxh5 gxh5 17. Rg1 f5 18. Bh6 Rf7 {[%csl Re1]}) 14. h4 Qa5 15. h5 a3 {[#]} 16.
b4 $1 {Winning time to execute the main idea.} (16. b3 Rfc8 17. Nd1 (17. Rc1
Bxg4 18. fxg4 Ncxe4) 17... Qxd2+ 18. Bxd2 $14) (16. bxa3 Rfc8 $132) 16... Qxb4
17. Rb1 Qa5 {[#]} 18. h6 (18. g5 {1-0 (32) Aloma Vidal,R (2428)-Silva,D (2223)
Batumi 2018} Nxh5 19. Nxh5 gxh5 20. Rxh5 f5) (18. Nb5 Ne8) (18. Bb5 Rfc8) 18...
Bh8 19. Nf5 $1 {After the inclusion of b4-Qb4 and Rb1, this thematic idea is
even stronger as now the weakness of Black's light squares is even bigger.}
Bxf5 (19... gxf5 $4 20. Bxc5 $18 {[%cal Gd2g5]}) 20. gxf5 Nfd7 $6 (20... Ne8
$142 {Protecting the pawn on d6.} 21. Nb5 Bf6 22. Qxa5 Rxa5 23. Bxc5 dxc5 24.
d6 $14) (20... Rfc8 21. Rb5 $16) 21. Nb5 $1 Qb6 (21... Qxd2+ 22. Kxd2 Ra6 23.
Nc7 Ra5 24. fxg6 fxg6 25. Bh3 $18) 22. Bh3 (22. fxg6 $1 fxg6 23. Bh3 Qd8 (23...
Rf7 24. Be6) 24. Be6+ Nxe6 25. dxe6 Nf6 26. Nxd6 Qe7 27. Nf5 Qxe6 28. Rb6 $18)
22... Qd8 (22... Nf6 23. Qc2 $18 (23. O-O $5)) 23. Nxd6 Qe7 24. Nb5 Bf6 25. d6
Bh4+ 26. Ke2 Qf6 27. Nc7 Rac8 28. Rbc1 {I wanted to provoke b6, so there would
be no tactic later connected with Rc7.} b6 (28... Rxc7 29. dxc7 Qa6+ 30. Kd1
$18) 29. Bg4 Kh8 30. Nd5 Qd8 31. f6 $2 {This is a huge practical mistake, even
though computers are not that critical about it. It just closes the position
and spoils the big part of the advantage. Moreover, now Black is getting some
counterplay.} (31. fxg6 $1 {was just winning a piece:} fxg6 32. Bxd7 (32. Bxc5
Rxc5 (32... bxc5 33. Bxd7 Bg5 34. Qc3 $18) 33. Bxd7 Bg5 34. Rxc5 Bxd2 (34...
bxc5 35. Qc3) 35. Rc8 $18) 32... Qxd7 33. Bxc5 (33. Rxh4 Qb5+) 33... bxc5 34.
Rxh4 $18) 31... Bg3 32. Ne7 (32. Qb4 $5) 32... Ra8 33. Rh3 $6 (33. Rc4 $5 {
[%cal Ga8a4] Not to be greedy, but to prevent any counterplay.}) 33... Bf4 34.
Bxf4 exf4 35. Qxf4 Ra4 $1 36. Rc3 $6 (36. Rh2 $1 {was very strong, to include
the rook back to the game:} Qa8 37. Ke3 {[%cal Gh2d2,Gh2c2]}) 36... Qa8 $6 (
36... Rb4 $1 37. Rxa3 b5 $1 {was unclear.}) 37. Bxd7 Qa6+ (37... Nxd7 38. Qe3)
38. Kf2 Nxd7 39. Rh1 Rb4 40. Kg3 Rb2 41. Qe3 b5 (41... Rxa2 42. Rhc1 Nc5 (42...
Qb5 43. Nd5) 43. d7 Rb2 44. Rxc5 bxc5 45. Qxc5 $18) (41... Re2 {would be a
nice trap:} 42. Qd3 $1 (42. Rxa3 $4 Qb5 $1 $19) 42... Qxd3 43. Rxd3 Rxa2 44.
Rc1 $18) 42. Rc6 $1 Qa5 43. Rhc1 b4 44. Nd5 (44. Rc8 $4 Qh5 $17) 44... Qa8 (
44... b3 45. Rc8 $18) 45. Nb6 Qe8 (45... Qa7 46. Rc8 $18) 46. Nxd7 Qxd7 47. Qc5
Rd2 48. Rc8 Rd8 49. e5 {Black resigned. After this game, I became the sole
leader and after some more adventures in the last rounds, I managed to win the
whole event!} 1-0

