{[#]} 22. Qe2 $1 $14 {[%csl Gg7] Thanks to the blocked bishop on g7 White has
a stable, long-terma advantage.} Bxe4+ 23. fxe4 Qf7 24. Rhf1 Qd7 25. g4 {
[%csl Gd5,Gc4,Ge4,Gg4,Gg5] Karpov is posting all his pawns on the opposite
color of his bishop.} Rxf1 26. Rxf1 Rf8 27. h3 h6 ({The trade:} 27... Rxf1+ {
does not help as after:} 28. Qxf1 h6 29. Bh4 $1 $16 {[%csl Bd8,Bb6,Bc7][%cal
Bh4d8,Yd7f7,Yf1f7,Bd8c7,Bc7b6] Black can never offer the queen swap due to his
vulnerable queenside.}) 28. Rxf8+ $1 {An important move.} ({In the line:} 28.
Bh4 Rf4 29. Bg3 Rxf1+ 30. Qxf1 Qf7 {[%csl Yc7,Yb6][%cal Yh4d8,Yd8c7,Bg8f7]} 31.
Qe2 a5 {Black is ready to swap off the bishops with Bg7-f6=}) 28... Bxf8 {
Now Karpov's plan is to trade the queens in the proper moment and enter a
winning bishop endgame provided he has a way to breakthrough.} (28... Kxf8 29.
Qf3+ Ke8 30. Bh4 $1 $16 {[%csl Gh4] is similar as the line from above.}) 29.
Bd2 ({Not:} 29. Be3 $6 Kg7 30. c5 $6 Qa4 $1) ({Nor:} 29. Bh4 Be7) 29... Kg7 {
[%cal Gf8e7,Ge7g5]} ({I believe that Hansen had to look for a way to bring his
bishop out. Small tactic might have helped him:} 29... a5 $5 30. b3 $16 {
[%csl Gh5][%cal Gh6h5,Gg8h7,Gf8h6] is given as large advantage by Karpov, but
he apparently missed:} Be7 $5 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Ge7g5]} 31. Bxh6 g5 32. h4 gxh4
33. g5 {[%cal Ge2h5,Gh5g6]} Qh3 $13 {when the black pieces are out and he has
good drawing chances.}) ({Naturally:} 29... g5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ge2f3,Gf3f5]
weakens the light squares to the limit.}) 30. c5 $1 {[%csl Ga6,Gf8][%cal Ge2a6]
Open the road for the white pieces.} dxc5 ({After:} 30... Qa4 31. c6 $5 {
[%csl Gc6,Rc7,Yb6][%cal Bc6c7,Ba5a4,Be3e2,Yd2e3,Ye3b6]} Be7 32. Bc3 Bg5 33. a3
$1 {[%csl Ya4][%cal Bb1a2,Bb2b3] The black queen is in trouble and Kb1-a2,
followed by b2-b3 would embarass it.}) ({Whereas:} 30... bxc5 31. Qxa6 $16 {
is hardly playable against the a-passer.}) ({The white king also makes it
through in case of:} 30... Qa4 31. cxb6 cxb6 32. b3 Qd4 33. Qe3 Qxe3 34. Bxe3
b5 $16 35. Kc2 Be7 36. Kc3 Bh4 37. Bd2 $1 Bf2 38. Kb4 Bb6 39. a4 bxa4 40. Kxa4
$1 $18 {(Karpov)}) 31. Qxa6 h5 ({There is no time for active counterplay:} 
31... c6 32. Bc3 cxd5 33. Bxe5+ Kh7 (33... Kf7 34. Qxb6 dxe4 35. Qf6+ Ke8 36.
Qxg6+ Kd8 37. Qb6+ Ke8 38. Qb8+ Kf7 39. Qc7 $18) 34. Qxb6 dxe4 35. Qc7 $18 {
(Karpov)}) 32. Qe2 hxg4 33. Qxg4 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Gc6c5,Ge6e5,Gc8c7,Gb7b6] The
grand plan remains to trade the queens.} (33. hxg4 $5 $16) 33... Qxg4 {A
principled mistake.} ({The last chance was to keep some dynamics in the
psoition with:} 33... Qb5 $1 34. Qf3 c6) 34. hxg4 Kf7 35. a4 ({The immediate:} 
35. Kc2 Ke8 (35... Ke7 $2 36. b4 $1 $16) 36. b4 cxb4 37. Kb3 Kd7 38. Bxb4 Bxb4
39. Kxb4 c6 {does not lead White anywhere (Karpov)}) 35... Ke8 36. a5 $5 ({
More accurate was:} 36. Bc3 $1 {[%cal Bb1c2,Bc2d3,Bd3c4,Bc4b5]}) 36... Kd7 ({
Hansen misses his last chace. The counter-intuitive:} 36... bxa5 $1 37. Bxa5
Kd7 38. Kc2 Kd6 39. Kd3 Bh6 40. Kc4 Bc1 41. Bc3 Be3 {might have helped him
create a fortress.}) 37. axb6 cxb6 38. Bc3 ({Not:} 38. b4 c4 39. b5 Bc5 40. Kb2
Bd4+ 41. Ka3 c3 $1 {(Karpov)}) 38... Bd6 (38... Kd6 39. b4 c4 40. b5 Kc5 41.
Bxe5 Kxb5 42. Kc2 Kc5 43. Kc3 b5 44. Bd4+ Kd6 45. Kb4 $18) 39. b4 $1 {Now
Karpov is merciles. This move practically wins a pawn.} cxb4 ({Or:} 39... c4 {
[%csl Yc4]} 40. b5 Ke7 41. Kc2 Kf6 42. Bd2 Bc5 43. Kc3 $18 {(Karpov)}) 40. Bd2
Kc7 41. Kc2 {A path has been opened for the white king and it munches both the
black b-pawns.} b5 42. Kb3 Kd7 43. Bxb4 Bc7 44. Bc3 Bd6 45. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2a3,
Gb4c3,Gc3b2]} b4 46. Bc1 Bc5 47. Bd2 Bg1 48. Kxb4 {[NB 7/f]} Bf2 49. Kc4 Bg1
50. Kd3 Bc5 51. Be3 Be7 52. Kc4 Ba3 $2 53. Bd2 $1 $18 {Winning thanks to the
zugzwang.} Be7 54. Bc3 Bd6 (54... Bf6 55. g5 $1 Bg7 56. Bb4 Kc7 57. Kb5 Kd7 58.
Kb6 Bh8 59. Bf8 Ke8 60. Kc7 Kxf8 61. d6 {(Karpov)}) 55. Bb4 Bb8 56. Kb5 Ba7 (
56... Bc7 57. d6 Bd8 58. Kc5 {(Karpov)}) 57. Bc5 Bb8 58. d6 $1 {1-0 Black
resigns.} 1-0

