{[#]In the following position the swap of the queens comes at once and the
current Guru of the KID suffers painful defeat:} 30. Qe6+ Kg7 31. Qd7+ Qf7+ (
31... Kf6 32. Qd8+ $18) 32. Qxf7+ Kxf7 33. a4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ga4,Ra5,Rb7,
Rc7,Rd6][%cal Gg2g4,Gh3h4,Gf1e2,Ge2f3,Gf3e4] In comparison to the previous
game White's task is much easier. He is prectically up a pawn on the kingside
and has plenty of opportunities to bring his king into the enemy camp.} Kf6 ({
Or else the a5 pawn might drop:} 33... c6 34. dxc6 bxc6 35. Bd2 $18 {[%csl Ga5]
}) 34. Ke2 Kf5 35. Kd3 h5 36. Bd2 b6 37. Ke3 Bf6 38. Kf3 Kg6 ({After:} 38... h4
{White will win in a similar fashion as in the game:} 39. Be1 Bg5 40. g3 hxg3
41. Bxg3 Be7 42. h4 Bf6 43. Bf2 Be7 44. h5 Kg5 (44... Bg5 45. Be3 Bxe3 46. Kxe3
Kg5 47. Ke4 Kxh5 48. Kf5 $18) 45. Ke4 Kxh5 46. Kf5 $18 {[%csl Gb6,Ga5][%cal
Gf5e6,Ge6d7,Gd7c7,Gc7b6] (Roiz)}) 39. g4 Bh4 (39... hxg4+ 40. Kxg4 $1 {[%cal
Gh3h5] in order to keep a more distant passer is important.}) 40. gxh5+ Kxh5 {
Next White is deflecting the opponent's pieces thanks to the outside passer.}
41. Ke4 (41. Be3 Bf6 42. Kf4 Bg5+ (42... Kg6 43. Kg4 $18) 43. Ke4 $18 {(Roiz)})
41... Kg6 42. Bf4 Bf6 43. Bg3 Kg5 ({Or:} 43... Bd8 44. h4 $18 {followed by
h4-h5}) 44. c5 $1 {[%cal Ge4d3,Gd3b5] A beautiful breakthrough that exposes
the vulnerability of the black pawns.} dxc5 ({Or:} 44... bxc5 45. Be1 $18 {
[%csl Ga5]}) ({Whereas:} 44... Be7 {is refuted thanks to:} 45. cxb6 cxb6 46.
Kd4 Kf5 47. Kc4 Ke4 48. Bf2 Bd8 49. h4 Kf3 50. Bd4 Bxh4 51. Bxb6 Be1 52. Kb5
Ke4 53. Bxa5 $18 {(Roiz)}) 45. Bxc7 b5 46. axb5 a4 47. d6 a3 48. d7 a2 (48...
Kg6 49. Be5 $18) 49. Be5 Bd8 50. Kd5 Kf5 51. Ba1 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

