{[#] The opposite situation can happen as well if White ends up with his weak
light-squared bishop on board.} 31. Nb3 $6 {[%csl Yf1] White helps the
opponent in reaching the ideal pure bishop endgame.} ({Better was:} 31. Be2 $15
{[%csl Gh1,Gg1][%cal Gd1h1]}) 31... Nxb3 32. axb3 Rc8 33. Rc1 $6 {Consistently
sticking to the wrong plan.} (33. Bd3 $15) 33... b4 34. Rxc8+ $2 ({The rooks
should have been kept! After} 34. Bc4 Kg7 35. Kc2 Rh8 36. Kd2 Rh2+ 37. Be2 {
[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc1c7]} Bb5 38. Re1 Kf6 39. Ke3 Bxe2 40. Rxe2 Rxe2+ 41. Kxe2
Kg5 42. Ke3 $10 {White survives the pawn endgame as:} Kh4 $4 {loses to:} 43. f4
$1) 34... Bxc8 35. Kc1 Kg7 36. Kd2 Kf6 37. Bb5 Kg5 {The last critical moment
of the game. The statical:} 38. Be8 $2 {loses.} ({Ivanov should have tried to
keep some dynamics in the position with:} 38. Ke3 $1 {Then the study-like
continuation:} Kh4 39. f4 exf4+ 40. Kxf4 g5+ 41. Ke3 g4 42. e5 g3 43. Bf1 dxe5
44. Ke4 Bh3 45. d6 g2 46. Bxg2 Bxg2+ 47. Kxe5 Bh3 48. Kf6 {[%cal Gf6e7]} Kg3
49. Ke7 Kf4 50. d7 Bxd7 51. Kxd7 Ke4 52. Kc6 Kd3 53. Kb5 Kc2 54. Kxa5 Kxb3 55.
Kb5 Kxb2 56. Kxb4 {leads to a draw.}) 38... Kf4 39. Bxg6 Kxf3 40. Bf5 Ba6 {
Now White loses as he cannot hold to both his weaknesses.} 41. Bg6 Kf4 {
[%csl Gd3][%cal Gh1e4,Gd2d3]} 42. Bf5 Bf1 43. Bh7 Bg2 44. Kd3 {[%csl Rb3,Re4]}
Bf3 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gf3d1,Gd1b3,Yd3c4] 0-1 White resigns due to the line:} 45.
Bg6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd1b3,Gb3a2,Ga2b1,Ga5a1,Gf3d5]} Bd1 46. Kc4 Be2# {[%csl
Yc4]} 0-1

