{[#]More pieces on the board hardly change the evaluation of the position.
White's position is clearly inferior any time the light-squared bishop stays
on board.} 29... Rf8 $1 30. Be2 ({Or:} 30. Kg2 $6 Nd3 $1 {[%csl Gd7,Gf4,Gf3]
[%cal Gd3f4,Gd3e5,Gd7h3]} ({Rather than:} 30... Bh3+ $6 31. Kxh3 Rxf3 32. Kg4
Rf2 33. Re1 Rxh2 34. Rxe3 Kf6 35. Ne4+ Nxe4 36. Rxe4 {when White should
survive. The rook endgame is the defender's best friend.})) 30... Rf2 31. Rg1 (
{Blakc is clearly better after:} 31. b4 axb4 32. axb4 Ne4 33. Rg1 Kh6 $17)
31... Kh8 $2 {A very poor choice of a square for the king.} ({Blakc would have
kept his advanatge with the obvious:} 31... Kh6 $1) 32. b4 axb4 33. axb4 Nb3 ({
The poor position on the black king starts to tell after:} 33... Ne4 $2 34.
Nxe4 Rxe2 35. Nf6 $18) (33... Na6 $6 {[%cal Gc5a6]} 34. Rb1 $14 {[%csl Ga6]
[%cal Gb1b4] is not good neither for Black.}) 34. Rf1 Rxf1+ ({Or:} 34... Bh3 $6
35. Rxf2 exf2 36. Bf1 $1 $10 {and once that the bishop leaves the board it is
a draw-} Bxf1 37. Nxf1 Nc1 38. Kg2 Nd3) 35. Bxf1 Bg4 36. Be2 Bxe2 37. Nxe2 {
The second best friend for the defender is the knight endgame:} Nd2 38. Kg2
Nxc4 39. Kf3 c6 $138 40. dxc6 bxc6 41. Nd4 c5 42. bxc5 {1/2-1/2 The game is a
draw.} 1/2-1/2

