[Annotator "GM Dejan Bojkov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r4bk1/3b3r/1q1p1n2/1N1Pp1p1/4PpP1/1Q3P2/1P2BNK1/2R2R2 b - - 0 29"]
[PlyCount "58"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{[#] Another most fundamental question in the KID endgames is who owes the
more active bishop in the opposite-coloured bishop endgames? Due to the locked
nature of the pawn chains this can be vital.} 29... Bxb5 $1 {At first Spasov
plays accurately.} ({Not:} 29... Rb8 30. Rc6 $1 Bxc6 31. dxc6+ Kh8 32. Qe6 $1
$16 {[%cal Ge6f6] (Khalifman)}) 30. Qxb5 Qxb5 31. Bxb5 Rb8 32. Bc6 Rxb2 33. Ra1
{But his next move is a mistake.} Be7 $2 {[%cal Ge7d8,Gd8b6] He does not have
the time to bring this piece out.} ({Correct was tp activate the knight at
once with:} 33... Nd7 $1 34. Rfb1 ({Then in the line:} 34. Bxd7 Rxd7 35. Rfb1
Rd2 $1 {the active black rooks compensate him for the poor minor piece.}) 34...
Rxb1 35. Rxb1 Nc5 {[%csl Be6,Yd3,Yf2,Yb7][%cal Bc5e6,Yc5d3,Yc5b7,Bh7a7,Bg8f7,
Bf8e7,Be7d8,Bd8b6] Once that the knight is out Black is safe.} 36. Ra1 Nb3 {
/\ Nd4= (Khalifman)}) 34. Rfb1 Rxb1 35. Rxb1 $16 {Now White instructively uses
his color superiority to penetrate the enemy position.} Kf7 36. Rb8 Rg7 37. Nd1
Rg8 38. Rb7 Rd8 39. Nc3 Nh7 40. Nb5 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Bh7g7,Bg7g8,Bg8d8,Yb5c7,
Yc7e6]} Nf8 {[%cal Gb5a7,Ga7c6]} 41. Na7 $1 {[%csl Ga7,Gc8][%cal Gc6b5,Ga7c6,
Gb7c7,Ga7c8] Intending either Bc6-b5 followed by Na7-c6, or Rb7-c7 and then
Na7-c8. Notice that Khalifman uses predominantly the light squares when
attacking, thus securing constant pressure. Spasov simply cannot use his
dark-squared bishop into the defence.} Kf6 42. Kf2 Ng6 43. Bd7 Nh4 44. Ke2 Ra8
45. Be6 Rd8 46. Nc6 Re8 {Now comes a nice set of small maneuvers that ruins
the Black's defensive set-up:} 47. Rd7 $1 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gd7d6]} Bf8 48. Rf7+ Kg6
49. Ra7 {[%cal Ge6f7,Gf7e8,Gf7g6]} Kf6 50. Bd7 $18 {[%csl Ye8,Yd8,Yb8,Ya8,Ye5,
Ye6][%cal Yc6d8,Yc6b8,Ya7a8,Yd7c8,Yc6e7,Yc6e5,Yd7e6]} Re7 51. Nxe7 Bxe7 52. Kf2
Bd8 53. Ra6 Ke7 54. Bf5 Bc7 55. Ke2 Ng2 56. Ra7 Kd8 57. Ra8+ Ke7 58. Rg8 {
1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

