{[#] Khalifman plays from the opposite side of the board here but his bishop
is once again superior therefore he does not hesitate to enter an OCB endgame
with:} 29... Qg4 $1 30. Qxg4 (30. Qh2 $2 Bf4) (30. Qe1 $2 Rxh3+) 30... hxg4 $17
31. Ra1 Rd2 32. Rgd1 g3 $1 {It is much more important to lock the black king
in the corner forever than to hunt pawns.} ({Black is correctly avoiding:} 
32... Rxd1+ $2 33. Rxd1 gxh3 $2 34. g3 $1 {[%cal Gd1a1,Ga1a8]}) 33. Rxd2 Bxd2
34. c5 ({After:} 34. Ra8+ Kg7 35. Rc8 Bxb4 36. Rxc7+ Kh6 37. Rxb7 Bc5 38. Rf7
Kg5 $1 $19 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gh4h8,Gh8a8,Ga8a1,Ga8a3,Gf7f1,Gc5f2,Gg5f4,Gf4e3] 
(Khalifman) the black pieces quickly take over.}) ({Nothing changes:} 34. Rb1 {
[%csl Gb4]} Kg7 35. Kg1 Rf4 {[%csl Rg1]}) 34... Bxb4 35. c6 bxc6 36. dxc6 Rf4
$1 37. Rb1 Bc5 38. Rb8+ Kg7 39. Rb7 Rf7 ({Of course not:} 39... Bb6 40. Rxb6
cxb6 41. c7) 40. Bc4 {For a moment it seems as Naumkin will force his opponent
into passive defense, but Khalifman had foreseen everything in advance.} d5 $3
$19 41. exd5 Rf4 $1 42. Be2 Re4 43. Rb2 Rd4 44. Rb3 Rd2 45. Bg4 Bf2 46. Rb7 Kf6
$1 47. d6 Rc2 $1 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

