{[#]} 26... e4 $3 {A very interesting idea! Now Black's structure is totally
bad for the endgame, all his pawns are on dark squares (the colour of his
bishop) and Black is a pawn down! But he is slightly better!} (26... Rab8) 27.
Nxe4 (27. fxe4 Bd4+ 28. Kh1 Rxf1+ 29. Rxf1 Bxb2 $15 {with ...Rb8-b4 to follow})
27... Bd4+ 28. Kh1 a4 (28... Rfb8 $5 29. b3 a4 {was quite good too! The
position is equal objectively, but Black might press here.}) 29. h4 (29. Rfc1
$1 Rfb8 30. Nc3 Rb4 31. b3 axb3 (31... Bxc3 32. Rxc3 Re8 33. Kg1 Re2 34. Ra1
Rb8 $15) 32. axb3 Ra3 33. Nb5 Raxb3 34. Rxb3 Rxb3 35. Nxc7 Kf7 36. Nb5 Be5 $15)
29... gxh4 30. Kh2 Rfb8 31. b3 axb3 32. axb3 {All moves starting from gxh4,
were quite logical and almost forced.} Ra2 (32... Ra3) 33. Rfd1 Kf7 {[%csl Gg2]
[%cal Gb8g8,Gg8g2] Now ...Rg8 is coming, the position is pleasant for Black
and White has to take measures to decrease Black's activity.} 34. Rd2 Ra3 $1
35. Kh3 Raxb3 36. Rxb3 Rxb3 37. Kxh4 Kg6 $5 38. Rc2 Rb1 $6 (38... h5 $5 {
This seems more strong to me.}) 39. Ng3 $1 {Somewhere here White offered a
draw, but I declined it and decided to play on.} h5 40. f4 $4 (40. Re2 $1 {
This move seems to give a draw finally.} Bf6+ 41. Kh3 Be5 42. Re4 Rc1 43. Rh4
Bf6 44. Re4 {and due to the e4 rook it is very hard to make any progress.} Kg5
45. Rh4) 40... Bf6+ 41. Kh3 Rb3 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4]} (41... h4 42. Ne2 Kf5 43. g4+
Ke4 44. g5 Bb2 $17 {But why does Black need such measures if he can win easily?
}) 42. Kh2 h4 43. Ne2 (43. Ne4 Kf5 $19 44. Nxf6 Kxf6 {[%csl Yc4,Yf4,Bc5,Bc7]
[%cal Bb6c5,Bc7d6,Bd6c5] and Black is winning. c4 and f4 are too weak and
White's king is cut off.}) 43... Kf5 44. Ra2 Rb4 $1 45. Ra8 Rxc4 46. Re8 Rb4
47. Re6 Rb3 $1 {The last finesse. Black is winning.} 48. g4+ hxg3+ 49. Nxg3+
Kg4 $1 50. Ne2 Rb2 51. Kg2 Be5 $1 52. Kf2 (52. Rg6+ Kf5 53. Rg5+ Kf6 54. Kf3
Bxf4 $19) 52... Bxf4 53. Re7 Kf5 54. Rf7+ Ke5 55. Kf3 Bd2 56. Rxc7 Kxd5 57. Ng3
Rb3+ 58. Kg2 Bf4 59. Ne2 Be5 60. Kf2 Ke4 61. Rh7 Rf3+ 62. Ke1 d5 63. Kd2 d4 64.
Rh4+ Kd5 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

