{[#] The idea of a pawn sacrifice should always be on the back of the KID
player's mind, no matter if he/she is attacking or defending. Istratescu's
position seems suspicious but he finds a way to bring his pieces into life:} 
25... Nc5 26. Nxc5 dxc5 27. Bxc7 Bc3 $1 $44 (27... Bxb5 28. cxb5 Rxc7 29. Bc4 {
[%csl Ge4]}) 28. Rc1 Bd4 29. Bg3 b6 $1 {Fixes the b5 pawn and prepares a7-a6.
It is equal after:} 30. Bd1 a6 {[%csl Gd4]} 31. Bc2 Bf5 32. bxa6 Rxa6 33. a4 e3
$1 34. Bxf5+ Rxf5 35. Rce1 exf2+ 36. Bxf2 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "Accentus Biel GM Tournament"]
[Site "lichess.org"]
[Date "2018.??.??"]
[Round "9.1"]
[White "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2808"]
[BlackElo "2843"]
[Annotator "GM Dejan Bojkov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1r4k1/1r3p1p/6p1/3RP3/5P1P/b5P1/6BK/3R4 b - - 0 38"]
[PlyCount "38"]
[EventDate "2020.??.??"]

{[#] Even an opposite-coloured bishop endgame with pawns on just one flank can
be problematic for the defender as it was proven in this top-game recently:} 
38... Be7 39. Kh3 (39. Rd7 Rxd7 40. Rxd7 Kf8 41. Bd5 Rd8) 39... Rc7 (39... h5 {
exposes the h5 pawn after} 40. f5 gxf5 41. Rf1) 40. h5 $1 {The way that
Mamedyarov mounts pressure during the game is impressive.} gxh5 {Trading the
pawn, which could have come to h6 with mating threats.} (40... g5 41. Rd7 Rxd7
42. Rxd7 Kf8 {there is} 43. f5 $1) (40... Kf8 {was passive defense was the
other way to try and hold.}) 41. f5 f6 42. e6 Rb3 (42... Kf8 $5) 43. Rd7 Rbc3
44. Ra1 Kg7 (44... Rxd7 45. exd7 Rd3 46. Ra8+ Kg7 47. Bc6 Rd6 48. Ba4 Rd4 49.
Re8 Kf7 50. Bb3+) 45. Ra8 Kh6 46. Re8 Bb4 {It is not clear how can White
improve further. If the bishop can find a good spot, he would be winning, but
it is not easy.} 47. Rb8 (47. Rh8 Be7 48. Be4 h4 $1 {with the idea} 49. Kxh4
Rxd7 50. exd7 Rc4 {with a draw.}) 47... Be7 48. Be4 R3c4 49. Bd5 R4c5 50. Be4
Rc4 51. Bd5 R4c5 52. Rb7 Rxd7 {Now he can.} 53. Rxd7 Ra5 54. Bc6 (54. Rxe7 Rxd5
55. Rf7 Rxf5 56. e7 Re5 57. Rxf6+ {is a draw.}) 54... Ba3 55. Rf7 {So far
Carlsen had defended perfectly and came very close to the draw.} Re5 (55...
Rxf5 56. e7 Bxe7 57. Rxe7 Rc5 58. Bf3 f5 {during the post mortem the players
were not sure about the evaluation, but Carlsen believed it should be drawn.})
56. Kh4 $1 {Depriving the black king of the g5 square. "I realized that was
it" (Carlsen)} (56. Rxf6+ {is what the world champion was calculating and it
should be defendable after} Kg5 57. Rf7 Bd6) 56... Bc1 $2 {Only this is the
crucial mistake. Apparently, Carlsen dismissed the position a tad too early.} (
56... Re2 57. Rxf6+ Kg7 58. Rf7+ Kh6 59. g4 Rh2+ 60. Kg3 {should win for White.
}) (56... Bc5 $1 57. Rxf6+ Kg7 58. Rf7+ Kh6 59. Bf3 (59. Bd7 Bd6 60. f6 Kg6)
59... Be3 {followed by Be3-g5+ Black seems to build sort of a fortress. For
example} 60. g4 (60. Bd1 Bg5+ 61. Kh3 Re3 62. Kg2 h4) 60... Bg5+ 61. Kg3 h4+
62. Kg2 Re3 {The draw seems the correct result here.}) (56... Bb4 $1 {is
similar to 56...Bc5.}) 57. e7 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

