{[#] The pawn structure which arises from the Classical KID is particularly
dangerous for the second player whenever an endgame arises. Often the only
thing White needs to do to claim large advantage is to take the sting out of
the opponent's attack with the swap of the major piece:} 29. Qb6 $1 Qxb6 30.
axb6 $16 Bd8 31. Ba5 {There is no more kingside attack, Larsen is in full
control of the opposite wing. In the play that follows he searches for a way
to break-through along the c-file and the swap of the light-squared bishops 
(even in exchange for a pawn) is his main idea.} Ne7 32. b3 Nc8 33. Nc4 Bh4 34.
Nd2 Bd8 35. Nc4 Bh4 36. Bf3 Nf6 37. Nd2 Ne8 38. Rc3 Ra8 39. Nc4 Bd8 40. Be2 Rb8
41. R1c2 Bh4 $2 42. Rh3 Bd8 43. g3 $1 fxg3 44. Rxg3 Bh4 45. Rh3 Bg5 46. Rhc3
Bd8 47. Bd1 Ne7 48. Bf3 Nc8 49. Nd1 Bxg4 50. Bxg4 Rxg4+ 51. Rg2 Rxg2+ 52. Kxg2
Nf6 53. Kf3 Nd7 54. Bb4 Ndxb6 55. Nxd6 Be7 56. Nxc8 Bxb4 57. Nxb6 Bxc3 58. Nxc3
Kf7 59. Nd7 Re8 60. Ke3 Re7 61. Nb6 Rc7 62. Kd3 Ke7 63. b4 Kf6 64. d6 Rh7 65.
Ncd5+ Ke6 66. d7 Rh8 67. Ne3 Ke7 68. Nf5+ Ke6 69. Kc4 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

