{[#] One more proof how bad these endgames can be for Black. The second's
player position is leaking, there is an enormous amount of holes into the
queenside, the last remaining pawn there sits on a light square and can be
easily attacked by the white pieces. On top of that, all black pieces lack
perspectives, the bishop is horrible and the knights are deprived of outposts.
} 39. Ra1 {[%csl Ra6,Ra7,Rb5,Rb6,Rb7,Rc6,Rc7,Yf8]} Kg6 40. Ra5 Nc7 41. Ba7 Rb7
42. Rc2 Kf6 43. Bf2 Rh7 {In such situations the only thing White needs to do
is to determine where do his pieces belong. Then he maneuvers towards the
ideal squares.} 44. Kg2 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gh3g1,Gg1e2,Ge2c3,Gc3b5,Yc1b3,
Yb3a5,Ye2c1]} Bh6 45. Ng1 Rh8 46. Bd3 Rhb8 47. Ne2 Nc8 48. Nc1 Ke7 49. Nb3 Kd7
50. Ra1 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra5,Rc6][%cal Rb3a5,Ra5c6] [><a5, c6]} Bf8 51. Na5 {
It's over without any flashy combinations or ideas.} Be7 52. Nxb7 Rxb7 53. Ra5
Bd8 54. Kf1 Be7 55. Ke2 Bd8 56. Kd2 Bf6 57. Kc1 Be7 58. Kb2 Bf6 59. Kb3 Bd8 60.
Rc1 Bf6 61. Rxc7+ Kxc7 62. Bxb5 Ne7 63. Be8 Kb8 64. b5 Nc8 65. Bc6 Bd8 66. Ra1
{1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

[Event "Amsterdam"]
