{[#] However, not all these endgames are as horrific for Black. In fact, if a
few pieces are traded and some files and diagonals are opened for the second
player he may well benefit once more from the overextended nature of the white
pawns.} 30... Qa7 $1 $15 {Topalov's pieces have enough room and the white
targets are far easier to be reached.} 31. b5 (31. Ra1 Qd4 $1 {(Topalov)})
31... axb5 32. Rxb5 Rxb5 33. Nxb5 Qc5 {[%csl Yd5,Re4][%cal Ye3e4,Yd4d5] It
becomes obvious that Black's co-operation against the white e4 pawn is easier
to achieve than White's attack against the alternative weakness on d6.} 34. Nc3
Nf6 35. Qf3 Kg7 36. g4 $5 {Active defense.} Qa3 $6 ({Gelfand's idea is
revealed in the line:} 36... Qd4 37. g5 Nh5 38. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Bg2g4,Bg4g5,
Yg4d7,Yd7d8,Yd8d7,Yd3c3] heading for a perpetual check.}) ({Better was} 36...
h6 $1 {(Topalov)}) 37. Kg2 Qb2+ 38. Kg1 Qc1+ 39. Kg2 Qd2+ 40. Kf1 h6 $2 ({
Instead Black had a more convincing way:} 40... h5 41. gxh5 Nxh5 42. Ne2 Nf4 $1
$17 {(Topalov)}) 41. Ne2 Qd1+ 42. Kf2 Qc2 43. Ke3 Qb1 ({Black doe snot mention
the strongest continuation:} 43... Nd7 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Bc5][%cal Gd7c5,Yc2d3,
Yd3e4] which quickly reaches the main target.}) 44. Ng3 Qe1+ 45. Kd3 Qg1 (45...
Nd7 46. h4 Nc5+ 47. Kc2) 46. h4 $1 {Gelfand generated enough counterplay, but
slipped in the very last hurdle.} ({Also good was:} 46. Qe3 $1 Qh2 47. Qa7+ Kh8
48. Qb8+ Ng8 49. Nf1 Qxh3+ 50. Ne3 $10) 46... Qb1+ 47. Ke2 Qc2+ 48. Kf1 $4 ({
Strong was:} 48. Ke1 $1 Qc1+ 49. Ke2 Qf4 50. h5 Nxg4 51. hxg6 {with a draw.})
48... Qc8 $1 $19 49. h5 Nxg4 50. Qe2 Qc1+ 51. Kg2 Qf4 52. hxg6 Kxg6 53. Qf3 (
53. Nf5 Kg5) 53... Kg5 54. Nf5 Qd2+ 55. Kg1 h5 56. Ng7 $2 ({Or:} 56. Nxd6 Qc1+
57. Kg2 Qc2+ 58. Kg1 Qc5+ $19 {(Topalov)}) 56... Qc1+ 57. Kg2 Qb2+ 58. Kg1 Qa1+
59. Kg2 Qa2+ {0-1 White resigns.} ({Due to:} 59... Qa2+ 60. Kg1 Qa7+) 0-1

