{[#] Another way for Black to prevent the generally bad endgames is to spice
up the game with a typical piece sacrifice as Gelfand did here:} 33... Bxg4 $1
{[]} ({The same old gloomy endgame expects Black in case of:} 33... Be8 $6 34.
Rc2 $1 $16) 34. fxg4 Nxe4 35. Rc2 Rxc2 36. Bxc2 Nf6 {For the sacrificed pawn
Gelfand weakened the enemy king and gave an impulse to his pawns. His pieces
are perfectly supporting the pawn chain and Black is doing great.} 37. Nc3 e4 (
37... Qd7 $5) 38. Nf2 e3 39. Nfe4 Ne8 {However, in the possible time-trouble
Black chooses wrongly when to step back.} ({After the strongest continuation:} 
39... e2 $3 40. Kf2 (40. Nxe2 Nxe4 41. Nd4 Ng3 42. Ne6+ Kf6 43. Bxg6 Kxg6)
40... f3 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gg6e5,Gf6g4]} 41. Qd4 Ne5 $17 {It would have been
Malanuik who is fighting for the draw.}) 40. Bd1 Ne5 41. Kg2 Kh6 42. b5 $1 {
and the Ukrainian GM prevailed later...} a5 (42... axb5 43. Nxb5 $18) 43. Qxa5
Qd7 44. b6 Nxg4 45. Qb5 Qc8 46. Qb4 Qd7 47. Qb5 Qc8 48. Qb4 Qd7 49. Nb5 $1 $18
Ne5 50. Nbxd6 Ng6 (50... g4 51. Nf6 $1 $18) 51. Qb5 $1 f3+ 52. Bxf3 Nf4+ 53.
Kg1 e2 $138 54. Bxe2 Qh3 55. Nf7+ $1 Kg7 56. Qb2+ Kg8 57. Bf3 $1 g4 58. Qe5
gxf3 59. Qxe8+ Kg7 60. Qe5+ Kf8 61. Qd6+ Kg8 62. Nh6+ {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

