{[%evp 0,95,29,20,30,0,34,34,34,34,34,43,42,37,39,37,37,28,35,37,12,33,47,-14,
-16,-46,-47,-41,-39,-53,-54,-55,-16,-34,-24,-31,-28,-32,-31,-14,-16,-8,-5,0,0,
-31,-37,-37,25,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,8,0,0,0,0,0,37,45,42,37,68,67,106,93,113,101,101,
109,139,152,159,118,154,183,185,162,170,244,248,192,204,194,192,226,250,278,
29989,29990,29991,29992,29993,29994]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 O-O
5. e4 d6 6. h3 e5 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bg5 Na6 10. Nd5 Rd6 11. Nd2 c6 {
This pawn structure on the other hand I consider favourable for Black. His
pawns are nicely covering all the central outposts and if White is not careful
enough he may end up facing a nasty black knight planted on the d4 outpost. Or
even two nasty knights on f4 and d4!} 12. Ne7+ {White goes for the two bishops,
but his dark squares are too weak, and this plan does not allow him any hint
of an advantage.} (12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Be3 (13. Bxf6 Rxf6 14. a3 {In the event
of:} (14. Be2 {the black knight reaches the d4-square by force -} Nb4 15. O-O
Nc2 16. Rad1 Nd4 $15) 14... c5 15. Be2 b6 (15... Nc7 $5) 16. Nb1 Rd6 17. Nc3
Rd4 {Instead of this Black had the simple plan:} (17... Nc7 $15 {both the
knights will occupy excellent advanced posts in the centre. However, the
difference between the power of the respective bishops determines the position
as being advantageous for Black.}) 18. Nb5 Rd8 19. Rd1 Rxd1+ 20. Kxd1 Bb7 {
1-0 Bruch,I (2330)-Pokrupa,M (2080)/Schwaebisch Gmuend 2001/CBM 080 ext (40)})
13... Nc7 (13... b6) 14. c5 Rd8 15. O-O-O Ne6 16. Bc4 Nd4 17. Nb3 b5 18. cxb6 (
18. Bd3 Nxb3+ 19. axb3 Be6 20. Kc2 a5 $15) 18... axb6 19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Bf4 b5
21. Bb3 Bb7 (21... Be6 $5 22. Bxe6 fxe6 23. Kb1 c5 $17) 22. e5 {0-1 Vasilescu,
L (2389)-Hristodorescu,D (2249)/Baile Tusnad 2000/EXT 2001 (30)}) 12... Kh8 13.
Nxc8 Rxc8 {[%csl Rf1]} 14. O-O-O Nc5 15. f3 Ne6 16. Be3 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gh5f4]} c5
{[%csl Ga7,Gd2][%cal Gc6c5] In this closed position the knights are more
useful than the bishops.} 17. Nb1 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3d5]} Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Rd8+ 19.
Kc1 {[%csl Ye3][%cal Bf6g8,Bg7h6] Now all Black needed to do to fix advantage
for good was to swap the correct pieces. In this case the dark-squared bishops.
He could have achieved this in various ways later.} Nh5 $15 {And Black was
totally dominant on the black squares.} 20. Nc3 Ng3 21. Rg1 {[%cal Gg7f6]} f5 (
21... Bf6 $1 $17 {[%csl Re3,Rf6][%cal Gf6g5]}) 22. exf5 Nxf5 23. Bd2 Rxd2 $2 {
There was no need to sacrifice anything when owing the long-term advantage.
And the punishment comes in the form of oversight by Black.} 24. Kxd2 Bh6+ 25.
f4 $1 {Apparently missed by Black.} (25. Ke1 Be3 26. Ne2 Bxg1 27. Nxg1 Ne3 $15)
(25. Kd3 Be3 26. Rh1 Nf4+ 27. Kc2 (27. Ke4 Bd4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf5g3,Gf5d6]
and mate.}) 27... Ng3 $19) 25... Bxf4+ 26. Kd3 Be3 27. Rh1 Nf4+ 28. Ke4 {
[%cal Gf5g3,Gg3h1]} Bc1 (28... Ng3+ 29. Kxe3 Nxh1 30. Ne4 {[%csl Gh1]} (30. Kf3
)) 29. Kf3 Bxb2 {Black is definitely not worse, but frustration started to
tell later and he lost.} 30. Ne4 Bd4 (30... Nd4+) 31. g3 Ne6 32. Bd3 Nd8 33. h4
Nc6 34. g4 Ng7 35. h5 gxh5 36. gxh5 h6 37. Nd6 Ne6 38. Kg4 Nf4 39. Be4 Nb4 40.
Rb1 Ne2 41. a3 Nc3 42. Rf1 Nxe4 43. Nxe4 Nc2 44. Rf7 Kg8 45. Rxb7 Nxa3 46. Kf5
Nxc4 47. Nf6+ Kf8 48. Ke6 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

