{This game was played in the final round of the Bulgarian Individual
Championship. Boris Chatalbashev was leading with 10/12, I was second with 9,
third was Momchil Nikolov with 8, and the fourth - Julian Radulski had 7
points. The spiciness of the situation was the fact that all the players who
were chasing the one in front of them had better tie-breaks. This meant that
in the event of a win, I could hope for the title (if Chatalbashev should lose)
. On the other hand, a possible draw could send me to third place. I needed to
play for a win with maximum stability. The exchange line of the KID did not
bother me.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. h3 e5 7. dxe5
dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bg5 Na6 10. Nd5 Rd6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Rc1 Bd8 13. c5 Re6
14. a3 Kg7 {A very useful prophylactic move. The king goes away from the
possible pin on the a2-g8 diagonal, thus preparing the advances f7-f6 or f7-f5.
} (14... c6 {is also logical. However, after:} 15. Bxa6 {it is better for
Black to capture the knight, rather than the bishop, as the following game
shows:} (15. Ne3 b6 {[%emt 0:00:53] 1/2-1/2 Grivas,E (2475)-Kotronias,V (2610)/
Karditsa 1996/ CBM} 16. cxb6 axb6 17. Bc4 Re8 18. Bxa6 Bxa6 19. Rxc6 Bb7 20.
Rc4 $15 {[%emt 0:00:43] 1/2 Grivas,E (2505)-Mozetic,D (2585)/Karditsa 1994/CBM}
) 15... bxa6 (15... cxd5 $142 16. Bd3 Re7 17. O-O Bd7 $11) 16. Ne3 {see the
game 1-0 Arnaudov,P (2195)-Urukalovic,R (2273)/Zadar CRO 2008 (48)}) 15. b4 (
15. h4 $6 {does not promise anything for White:} c6 16. Bxa6 (16. Ne3 b6 17.
Bc4 {White wins a pawn, but the powerful bishops and the insecure position of
the enemy king provide more than sufficient compensation to Black.} Re7 18.
Bxa6 Bxa6 19. cxb6 axb6 20. Rxc6 Bb7 21. Rc4 b5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gd8a5]} 22.
Rc5 Bxe4 23. Rxb5 (23. Rxe5 Ba5+ 24. b4 $140 Rxe5 25. Nxe5 Bc7 $17) 23... Rc8
$36) 16... cxd5 17. Bd3 dxe4 (17... Re7 $5) 18. Bxe4 f5 19. Bd5 Re7 20. Ke2 {
And White already experienced difficulties, since the line:} (20. O-O e4 21.
Nd4 Re5 22. Bb3 Bxh4 {loses a pawn (Ilincic)}) 20... e4 21. Nd2 Re5 $15 {
0-1 Grivas,E (2505) -Ilincic,Z (2530)/Varna 1994/EXT 1997 (33)}) (15. Ne3 $5 {
is worth a try in a practical game. Now:} c6 {can transpose, but} (15... Nb8 {
is an interesting alternative-} 16. Bc4 (16. h4 Nc6 17. Bc4 Re8 18. h5 Nd4 $36)
16... Re8 17. O-O f6 18. Rfd1 c6 $11 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gb8d7,Gd7f8,Gf8e6] should
give good play to Black.}) 16. Bc4 (16. Bxa6 bxa6 {transposes to Arnaudov,P 
(2195)-Urukalovic,R (2273)/Zadar CRO 2008 (48), where the rook on e6 was a
target for the white knights.}) 16... Re7 17. Bxa6 bxa6 18. Nc4 Bc7 19. Kd2 a5
20. Kc3 Ba6 21. Nfd2 Rb8 22. Rhd1 a4 $11 {is a line given by Ilincic in the
Chess Informant.}) 15... c6 16. Bxa6 cxd5 17. Bd3 Re7 18. O-O f5 {[%csl Rd3,
Gd5,Re4,Ge5,Rf3,Gf5][%cal Gd5e4,Ge5e4,Gf5e4] This is a better version of the
game Kapnisis-Kotronias, but still quite unclear. If Black wants safe equality,
he can opt for:} (18... dxe4 19. Bxe4 f5 20. Bd5 e4 21. Nd4 Re5 22. Bb3 Bf6 $11
) 19. exd5 e4 20. d6 Rd7 {I felt that this is the best choice.} (20... Rf7 21.
Ne5 (21. Bxe4 fxe4 22. Ne5 Rf5) (21. Bc4 $1 exf3 22. Bxf7 Kxf7 (22... fxg2 $2
23. Rfd1 {[%cal Rd6d7]}) 23. b5 Bg5 24. Rc2 Bd7 25. c6 bxc6 26. bxc6 Rc8 27. h4
$1 {[%csl Rc1,Rd8]} Bxh4 28. Rfc1 Be6 29. Rb1 fxg2 30. Rb7+ Kg8 31. d7 $18)
21... exd3 22. b5 (22. Nxf7 Kxf7 23. Rfd1 Bg5 24. Rc3 Bd7 (24... d2 25. g3 Bd7
26. f4 Bf6 27. Rd3 a5 $15)) 22... Rf8 23. d7 d2 24. Rc2 Ba5 25. c6) 21. Ne5 ({
During the game I mainly studied} 21. Bxe4 fxe4 22. Ne5 Bf6 {[%cal Rf6b2,Rb2a3,
Ra3d6]} 23. Nxd7 Bxd7 24. Rfe1 Bc6 {when the white passed pawns are blocked,
and Black is already threatening to start picking them up.}) (21. Bb5 exf3 22.
Bxd7 fxg2 23. Kxg2 Bxd7 $17) 21... exd3 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Rd3d2]} 22. b5 d2 (
22... Ba5 $143 23. Nc4 Bd8 24. c6 (24. Rfd1 $5) (24. Ne5 $11) 24... bxc6 25.
bxc6 Rf7 26. Rfd1 Ba6 27. Ne5 $14) 23. Rc2 Bf6 {I disliked the fact that in
the lines starting with:} (23... Bg5 24. f4 $6 (24. h4 $142 $5 Bxh4 (24... Bf4
$2 25. Nxd7 Bxd7 26. c6 bxc6 27. bxc6 Be6 28. d7 Bc7 29. Rxd2 $18) 25. Rxd2 $14
) 24... Bxf4 25. Nxd7 Bxd7 26. c6 bxc6 27. bxc6 Rc8 $2 (27... Be6 $142 28. d7
Kf6 $17 {[%cal Gf6e7,Gf4c7]}) 28. cxd7 {[%cal Rd7d8] the d8-square is not
protected and Black loses an exchange.}) 24. f4 {This looks like a mistake to
me now. In the line-} (24. Nxd7 Bxd7 25. c6 Rc8 $1 26. c7 Bxb5 {Black wins the
pawn, but the computer shows that the things are far from clear-} 27. Rb1 Bg5 {
It looks like that Black should play the complicated position after:} (27...
Bd7 28. Rxd2 b5 $13) 28. h4 Bf4 29. g3 Bxd6 (29... Ba4 30. d7 (30. gxf4 Bxc2
31. d7 Bxb1 32. d8=Q {leads also to an edge for White}) 30... Bxd7 31. gxf4 Bc6
32. Rxd2 Rxc7 $14) 30. Rxd2 Rxc7 31. Rxb5 Bxa3 32. Rbd5 $16) 24... Rd8 25. Rxd2
Bxe5 26. fxe5 Bd7 27. e6 (27. a4 Kf7 $17 {[%cal Rf7e6,Ra8c8]}) 27... Bxe6 28.
c6 Rac8 (28... bxc6 29. bxc6 Rac8 30. Rc1 Bd7 31. c7 Re8 {could have kept the
bishop alive.}) 29. Re1 (29. Rc1 Bd7 30. Rdc2 bxc6 31. bxc6 Be8 32. d7 Bxd7 33.
cxd7 Rxc2 34. Rxc2 Rxd7 $17) 29... Kf7 {And not:} (29... Kf6 $2 30. d7 Rc7 31.
Rd6 $18 {[%csl Re6]}) 30. d7 Rc7 31. Rde2 Bxd7 32. Re7+ Kf6 33. cxd7 {Playing
for mate fails -} (33. Rxh7 bxc6 34. Ree7 cxb5 35. h4 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rh7f7]}
Rc1+ 36. Kh2 Be6) 33... Rdxd7 {I have managed to emerge a pawn ahead from the
complications. However, a rook endgame always gives a lot of drawing chances
for the defender.} 34. R7e6+ Kg5 35. b6 $6 {White wants to exchange both the
pawns on the queen's flank, but he lacks the time.} (35. R1e2 $17 {securing
the second rank should have been preferred.}) 35... axb6 36. Rxb6 Rc2 37. Re3 (
37. Rb3 Rdd2 38. Rg3+ Kf6 $19 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Rf5f4,Rh7h5]}) 37... Rd1+ 38.
Kh2 f4 $19 39. Rf3 Rdd2 40. Rb5+ Kh6 41. Rxf4 Rxg2+ 42. Kh1 Rh2+ 43. Kg1 Rxh3
44. a4 Rc7 45. Rfb4 {Somewhere around here Chatalbashev resigned his game,
