{This is probably the most important structure in the Fianchetto Variation.
There are two factors that make White's position better from a statical point
of view: 1) the space advantage provided by the pawns on c4 and e4 2) the weak
d6-pawn In order to compensate for the statical problems, Black should play
very dynamically. He usually tries to combine the pressure on e4 with
queenside activity. The g7-bishop provides a number of tactical possibilities
on the dark squares. Black's counterplay is usually based on the following
ideas: 1) putting the knights on c5 and e5 with the idea to invade via the
d3-square. 2) going for a queenside activity by means of ...a7-a5-a4 followed
by ...Qa5-b4 3) weakening the dark squares on the queenside with ...h7-h5-h4.
This strategy works very well when White has already played h2-h3 In most of
the cases, Black combines these three approaches. Of course, having less space,
Black tries to exchange minor pieces (except the g7-bishop) White's strategy
is simpler. Before anything else, White needs to restrict Black's counterplay.
After doing so, he could combine the queenside expansion (by means of b2-b4)
with pressure on d6. A typical idea is to deflect the d6-pawn by playing b2-b4
followed by c4-c5. After such an exchange, White enjoys a free hand in the
centre. For instance, he can expand by playing f2-f4 followed by e4-e5 and
Nc3-e4-d6. Quite obviously, having more space, White should refrain from
exchanging minor pieces.}  *

