{We can see a typical position in which things went wrong for Black. A typical
sign for such a bad scenario are passive moves like ...Re7, ...Bd7, and ...Qc7.
Whenever Black is forced to go for such decisions, White's static advantage
usually grows. In the game, White opted for his usual idea -} 16. b4 {gaining
space on the queenside.} Ne6 17. Nde2 {No exchanges!} Rae8 $6 {Quite a dubious
decision. Since the e4-pawn is safely protected, Black's rooks are useless on
the e-file.} 18. Red1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc2d2,Gd1d6] White is threatening Qd2
on the next move. It turns out that the d6-pawn cannot be easily protected.
Black was forced to accept even more passive position.} Rf8 19. Qd2 Ne8 20. f4
{We have the dream position for all the fianchetto players. As we know,
White's most typical plan in this position is based on the advance c4-c5.} f5 {
Black goes for a desperate counterplay. Due to the passivity of his pieces,
however, he is not ready for opening the position up.} 21. c5 $1 dxc5 22. bxc5
fxe4 23. Nxe4 {[%cal Ge4d6] As always, the knight is ready to occupy the
d6-square.} Bc8 24. Nd6 Rd7 25. Qb4 {White enjoys complete domination.} Kh8 26.
Nc3 Nxd6 27. cxd6 c5 28. dxc7 Rxd1+ 29. Nxd1 cxb4 30. Rxb4 Nxc7 31. Bxa7 {
Afterwards, White easily converted his extra pawn.} Na6 32. Rb1 Rf7 33. Ne3 h5
34. h4 Be6 35. a3 b5 36. Bb6 b4 37. axb4 Ba2 38. b5 Nc7 39. Rb4 Bc3 40. Ra4 1-0

