{After understanding the basic ideas of the structure, we shall take a look at
several examples which feature White's most promising positional idea - the
advance c4-c5. Let's take a look at the position on the diagram. White managed
to restrict Black's attempts to obtain a counterplay. Therefore, it's time to
expand on the queenside.} 18. b4 Qc7 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf6g4]} 19. Rc1 {[%csl
Gc3][%cal Gc1c7] Important move. Besides overprotecting the c3-knight, White
also puts the rook against Black's queen.} a5 20. a3 axb4 21. axb4 Ra8 22. Qb3
h5 {A typical idea for this pawn structure. Black is planning to weaken the
dark squares by means of ...h5-h4.} 23. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gf4c7] The most
precise continuation. By creating an opposition along the diagonal h2-b8,
White prepares the thematic advance c4-c5.} Nh7 24. c5 $1 {Finally, everything
is ready for this advance. As we have already pointed out, the exchange of the
d6-pawn is a powerful position idea in such structures. Afterwards, White can
start advancing his central pawns.} Be5 25. cxd6 Qxd6 26. Rcd1 Qc7 27. Bxe5
Rxe5 28. f4 $18 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gc3e4] Black is already strategically lost. White
is planning to proceed with e4-e5 followed by Nc3-e4-d6. Afterwards, Black
would be helpless against the mobile kingside majority.} Re7 29. e5 Nb6 30. Ne4
Rd8 31. Rd6 Kg7 32. Red1 Ree8 33. Qc3 Kg8 34. Qd4 Rxd6 35. Nxd6 Re6 36. Bd3 Nd5
37. f5 gxf5 38. Bxf5 Rxd6 39. exd6 Qxd6 40. Rf1 Nhf6 41. Bb1 Qe7 42. Kh2 Kg7
43. b5 Ne3 44. Rc1 c5 45. Qxc5 Qe6 46. Qg5+ Kf8 47. Kg1 h4 48. Qh6+ Kg8 49. Re1
1-0

