{The next example shows an alternative way of preparing the advance c4-c5. In
this position, instead of playing the normal 13.Bf4, White opted for} 13. Nb3 {
The idea of this move is to answer} Ne6 {with} 14. Na4 {[%cal Gc4c5] ,thus
preparing the advance c4-c5. Even though this idea is not that convincing, you
can use it under favourable circumstances. The next few moves are quite
logical.} Rb8 15. c5 dxc5 16. Nbxc5 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 {The character of the
position is already clarified. White's idea is pretty much clear - he wants to
proceed with f2-f4 followed by e4-e5. Therefore, Black should play very
dynamically.} Bf8 18. Nxe6 Bxe6 19. b3 b5 20. Nc3 Bg7 ({Another decent option
would have been} 20... a4 {with the idea to open the a-file for the rook.}) 21.
Be3 Red8 $6 {This move turns out to be a bit slow. Now, White has enough time
to transfer his knight to d4.} ({Better would have been} 21... a4 22. Ne2 axb3
23. axb3 Bc8 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c5] with the idea to put pressure on e4 by means
of ...Bb7 followed by ...c6-c5.}) 22. Ne2 a4 $6 {It is already too late for
this advance.} (22... Nd7 {with the idea to answer} 23. Nd4 {with} Bxd4 24.
Rxd4 c5 25. Rd6 c4 {when Black keeps the balance.}) 23. Nd4 axb3 24. axb3 Bd7
25. Rbc1 Rdc8 26. e5 $18 {White is winning a pawn by force and obtains a
decisive advantage.} Nd5 27. Nxc6 Bxc6 28. Bxd5 Be8 29. e6 Bf6 30. exf7+ Bxf7
31. Bxf7+ Kxf7 32. Rd7+ Ke6 33. Rxc8 Rxc8 34. Rb7 1-0

