{This is another very important structure. This time, Black has a pawn on c7 
(instead of c6). Since the d6-pawn is protected, Black can focus on his
kingside play. A typical way of playing on the kingside is the manoeuvre...
Re8-e5-h5. Before going for this idea, Black usually puts his queen's knight
on c5 and the bishop on d7 (sometimes even ...Qc8). With a correct play,
however, White manages to neutralize this aggressive approach. As White
usually plays h2-h3, Black often tries to put a simultaneous pressure both on
h3 and e4. A typical way to execute this idea is the move ...h7-h6 followed by
the manoeuvre...Nc5-e6-g5. The dark-squared strategy introduced by the advance
...h7-h5-h4 remains valid in this structure as well. Now, let's discuss the
drawbacks of Black's setup. With the pawn being on c7, Black faces the
following problems: 1) bad control of the centre (White can make use of the
squares b5 and d5) 2) the c7-pawn restricts the mobility of the queen As
always, White's priority is to restrict Black's counterplay. Once again, he
would expand on the queenside by means of Rb1 followed by b2-b4. As I have
mentioned in the explanation of Structure 1, avoiding exchanges of minor
pieces is a normal strategy in such positions. In many cases, White can use
the d5-square which is the perfect outpost for the knight. Additionally, we
shall pay attention to the possible modifications of the pawn structure. For
example, if Black plays ...c7-c6, we would transpose to Structure 1. Sometimes,
Black plays ...c7-c5 followed by ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5, thus reaching
structure 3. It is important to remember that in such positions the move ...
a7-a5 is well met by Ndb5, making use of the fact that the black pawn is not
on c6. The move Ndb5 usually paralyzes Black's queenside. Afterwards, White
would follow with Bf4 and e4-e5. Generally speaking, White's main task is to
prevent any possible counterplay. If he manages to do so, Black's position
will start collapsing. In the model game, you shall see how White neutralizes
each possible setup for Black.}  *

