{In the next example, we shall take a look at Black's attempt to apply a
dark-square strategy in this structure. Contrary to the previous example,
instead of playing 11...Bd7, in this game Black started with} 11... a5 {
Securing the knight and keeping a certain degree of flexibility regarding the
development of the c8-bishop. For example, if later Black goes for ...c7-c6,
the bishop wouldn't be well placed on d7. The last move, however, has an
important drawback - it weakens the b5-square. White can immediately make use
of this weakness by playing} 12. Ndb5 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc1f4,Ge4e5,Gb5d6]
It turns out that Black can no longer play ...c7-c6 due to the weakness of the
d6-pawn. Later on, White is planning to follow with Bf4 and e4-e5. It is not
easy for Black to coordinate his pieces. Since the queen is restricted by the
c7-pawn, Black would face problems to connect the rooks. In order to solve his
space problems, he goes for the following exchange operation -} Bd7 13. Bf4
Bxb5 14. cxb5 Nfd7 15. Qc2 {The pawn structure has changed. White has a pair
of bishops and the possibility to put pressure on the c-file. Additionally,
d5-square is an important outpost that can be used by the knight. On the other
hand, Black has better control of the dark-squares - all his minor pieces can
control the dark squares while only 2 white pieces can do so. Therefore, Black
should apply a dark-square strategy by starting with} h5 {[%cal Gh5h4]
Planning to weaken the dark squares with ...h5-h4.} 16. Rad1 $6 {White allows
his opponent to execute the dark-square strategy,} ({The most accurate would
have been} 16. Be3 $1 h4 17. g4 g5 {[%cal Gg7e5,Gc5e6] Black is ready to take
full control of the dark squares with Be5 followed by Ne6. White, however, has
a powerful resource at his disposal -} 18. e5 $1 {You need to make use of the
light-squares, even at the price of a pawn.} Rxe5 19. Rad1 Rb8 20. Re2 Nf8 21.
Red2 $44 {with more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 16... h4 17. g4
Ne6 18. Be3 Be5 19. Nd5 g5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4] This blockade on the dark squares
is Black's dream. White players should definitely avoid such positions. The
position is equal. Neither player can make progress.} 20. Rf1 a4 21. f4 gxf4
22. Nxf4 Nxf4 23. Bxf4 Bxf4 24. Rxf4 Ne5 25. Qf2 Re6 26. Rf5 c5 27. Rf1 Qe7 28.
Qd2 Rg6 29. Rh5 Kg7 30. Rff5 1/2-1/2

