{This structure is typical for the so-called Gallagher Variation. As I have
pointed out in my explanation of Structure 2, this structure arises when Black
plays ...c7-c5 followed by ...a7-a6. The position is quite similar to the
Benoni Defence, the difference being that White has a pawn on c4 (instead of
d5). I think that this difference is in White's favour due to the fact that
the d6-pawn is more vulnerable now. Statically speaking, White enjoys a clear
advantage because of the following factors: 1) more space 2) strong outpost on
d5 3) vulnerable d6-pawn As always, only a very dynamic and concrete play
would compensate Black for the statical problems. Usually, he goes for an
immediate queenside activity by means of ...b7-b5. The d6-pawn is often being
sacrificed. It is important to mention that the queenside play is perfectly
supported by the g7-bishop. If Black doesn't execute the advance ...b7-b5 on
time, then White would stop it by means of a2-a4. Afterwards, White can
combine the pressure on d6 with a kingside activity which is usually initiated
with f2-f4-f5. When Black gets his queenside play going, White's best strategy
is to respond in the centre by putting pressure on d6. Even though, the
arising complications seem to favour White, a lot of precision is required by
both players.}  *

