{[#] Now, we shall examine some typical ideas in the so-called Gallagher
variation which starts with Black's last move 10...a6. This time, Black has
different ideas concerning the future of the c7-pawn. Actually, the last move
is preparing for a Benoni-like queenside counterplay. In the next few moves,
Black is planning to follow with ...Rb8, ...c7-c5, and ...b7-b5, with or
without the inclusion of ...Ne5. If White decides to stop the advance ...b7-b5
with a2-a4, Black can opt for ...a6-a5, thus making the c5-square available
for the knight (forever). In the game, I think that White challenged Black's
concept in the most principled way -} 10... a6 11. Be3 Rb8 12. b3 $1 {This is
an important prophylactic move. Otherwise, in many lines, the move ...Ne5
would come with a tempo. Black goes for his typical queenside play with} c5 13.
Nde2 b5 {This move invites interesting tactical complications.} 14. Qxd6 b4 15.
Na4 $1 {White goes for a positional exchange sacrifice.} ({The alternative} 15.
e5 $6 {is well met by} Nh5 16. f4 bxc3 17. g4 Nxf4 18. Bxf4 c2 19. Rac1 Bb7 {
½-½ (45) Petrosyan, T (2469)-Iordachescu, V (2600) Al Ain 2015 with mutual
chances. Actually, this is the kind of position Black is aiming for in the
Gallagher System.}) 15... Nxe4 {Of course, Black should accept the challenge.
The next sequence is pretty much forced -} 16. Bxe4 Bxa1 17. Rxa1 Rxe4 18. Nxc5
Re8 19. Rd1 Qe7 20. Qxe7 Rxe7 21. Nf4 Nxc5 22. Bxc5 Rd7 23. Nd5 {The dust has
settled. The piece activity as well as the weak dark squares in Black's camp
provide White with more than enough compensation for the exchange. Even though,
White didn't manage to win the game, he advantage is obvious.} Kg7 24. Bd4+ f6
25. Bxf6+ Kf7 26. Be5 Rb6 27. Rd4 Re6 28. Rf4+ Ke8 29. Nf6+ Rxf6 30. Rxf6 Rd1+
31. Kh2 Bb7 32. g4 Rd2 33. Kg3 a5 34. Rb6 Bc8 35. c5 Rxa2 36. Rb8 Kd8 37. Bf6+
Kc7 38. Be5+ Kd8 39. Bf6+ Kc7 40. Be5+ Kd8 1/2-1/2

