{[#] The next example shows what could happen if Black makes even one passive
move in the structure with a pawn on c5. In this position, instead of the
active 13...b5, Black decided to protect the d6-pawn with} 13... Qc7 {Such a
passive move is totally wrong in this pawn structure. Only very active play
can compensate for the statical weaknesses provoked by the advance ...c7-c5.
In this position, White just plays} 14. a4 $1 {thus obtaining a strategically
winning position. In the future, White's idea is to combine the pressure on
the d6-pawn with a kingside attack. Black is doomed to passivity.} b6 15. Qd2
Bb7 16. f3 Ne5 17. Rad1 Rbd8 18. Bg5 $1 {Further disturbing Black's
coordination before going for the advance f3-f4-f5.} Rd7 19. f4 $1 Nc6 20. f5 {
This is a thematic way to destroy Black's defence in such structures. In the
game, after} Nd4 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. fxg6 $18 {White was already winning.} Bg7
23. gxh7+ Kh8 24. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 25. Kh1 f6 26. Ne2 Be5 27. Nf4 Rg7 28. Qe2 Rg5 29.
Nh5 Qxh7 30. Nxf6 Bxf6 31. Rxf6 Rxe4 32. Qf2 Rg8 33. Kh2 Reg4 34. Rf7 R4g7 35.
Rxg7 Qxg7 36. Bxb7 Qxb7 37. Qf6+ Kh7 38. Rxd6 1-0

