{This structure is typical for many lines in King's Indian Defence. In the
model games, I examine this structure with and without ...exd4 included. By
going for ...c7-c6, ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5, Black has two main ideas: 1) gain
space on the queenside 2) reduce White's control of the centre by eliminating
the c4-pawn Of course, such an approach includes some positional problems as
well. For example, in many lines White makes use of the queenside weaknesses
created by ...b7-b5. Another problem is that this strategy is rather
time-consuming. Instead of developing his pieces, Black makes 3 pawn moves. As
you are going to witness in the model games, White's best setup is Qc2
followed by Rd1, putting the rook against the black queen. White's most
thematic idea is the break c4-c5. As often happens in the Fianchetto Variaiton,
after deflecting the d6-pawn, White expands in the centre by means of f2-f4
followed by e4-e5. My conclusion is that this structure is difficult for Black.
}  *

