{So far, we have been dealing with a number of ways to handle this position
with Black - 8...c6 and 8...exd4 followed by different setups. Sometimes,
Black prepares the advance ...b7-b5 without clarifying the situation in the
centre. In the game Black played} 8... a6 9. h3 b5 {This idea can be seen in
many King's Indian variations. Deflecting the c4-pawn would tremendously
reduce White's central control. Additionally, Black's queenside pieces would
immediately take part in the game. My experience has taught me that White's
best setup against this idea is Qc2 followed by Rd1, immediately taking
advantage of the restricted position of the black queen. Bromberger took this
direction} 10. Qc2 c6 {Black should take the d5-square under control.} ({
One of the ideas behind 10.Qc2 is to answer} 10... b4 11. Nd5 {since the
e4-pawn is protected. A possible continuation would be} Nxd5 12. cxd5 exd4 13.
Rd1 {[%cal Gf3d4] White will definitely regain the d4-pawn. After doing so, he
will be ready to take advantage of Black's queenside weaknesses provoked by
the move ...b7-b5.}) ({In such structures, you should never be afraid of} 10...
bxc4 {which is typically well met by} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Be3 {[%csl Rc4][%cal
Gf3d2,Gd2c4] Obviously, White will regain the pawn by means of the manoeuvre
Nd2-c4. Afterwards, Black cannot easily solve his structural weaknesses.}) 11.
Rd1 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gd6e5,Gf3e5,Gd1d8] The opposition along the d-file is very
annoying for Black. White is currently planning to win the e5-pawn.} Qe7 (11...
b4 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Na4 Qa5 14. Be3 Rb8 15. b3 $16 {[%cal Ga2a3]}) 12. c5 $1 {
One should remember this thematic advance. The structural modifications in the
centre would favour White since he is better developed and has more active
pieces.} dxc5 ({Even worse is} 12... exd4 {when after} 13. cxd6 Qxd6 14. Nxd4 {
[%cal Gc1e3,Gf2f4,Ge4e5] White's central pawns will start rolling.}) 13. dxe5
Ne8 14. Bg5 Qe6 15. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Ge2f4]} Nxe5 16. Qxc5 f6 $2 {This is a huge
positional mistake which allows White to stabilize his advantage.} ({Black
should have preferred} 16... Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Nf6 {Keeping chances for a
counterplay.}) 17. Be3 Rf7 18. Nf4 Qc4 $2 {Another mistake in a difficult
position.} ({More tenacious would have been} 18... Qe7 19. Qxe7 Rxe7 20. Nxe5
fxe5 21. Nd3 {[%cal Gd3c5,Gd1d2,Ga1d1] when a huge advantage for White.}) 19.
Rd8 Bb7 20. Rad1 $18 {Black is completely tied. White is already winning.} Bf8
21. Nxe5 Qxc5 22. Bxc5 fxe5 23. Ne6 Be7 24. Bxe7 Rxe7 25. Nc5 Rxd8 26. Rxd8 Kf7
27. Rb8 Nd6 28. f4 Kf6 29. Nd3 Nf7 30. fxe5+ Nxe5 31. Nc5 1-0

