{This important structure arises when White's d-pawn is exchanged for Black's
c-pawn. You can see the same pawn formation in many lines of the English
Opening. White has a static advantage which is based on two factors: 1)
d5-outpost secured by the c4-pawn 2) pressure on the long diagonal h1-a8 In
such positions, White's priority should be installing a knight on d5. Since
Black cannot live with such a knight he will either exchange the knight or
chase it away by means of ...e7-e6. In the first case, White will recapture
with a pawn (ideally exd5 if the move e2-e4 has been played), thus enjoying a
considerable space advantage. If Black goes for ...e7-e6, then the d6-pawn
will become vulnerable. Another approach for Black is to prepare the advance ..
.b7-b5. This usually happens with ...Bd7, ...a7-a6, and ...Rb8. The advance ...
b7-b5, however, would considerably weaken the queenside. In some lines, the
c6-knight would become vulnerable. As a rule, White tries to counter this
strategy by playing in the centre. All these ideas are well illustrated in the
two model games dedicated to this structure.}  *

