{[%evp 0,93,20,27,20,6,32,11,11,11,11,28,28,28,42,35,32,9,44,39,22,20,15,22,26,
25,16,18,8,27,31,27,28,22,57,66,78,65,57,67,45,77,71,59,59,44,50,23,20,10,13,
13,25,33,33,25,29,4,17,16,26,0,7,5,32,40,57,56,49,49,57,54,64,64,59,36,66,20,
31,24,102,121,140,76,159,159,245,245,247,247,359,402,497,503,498,506] Finally,
we shall take a look at some important structures which arise in the line 6...
Nc6 followed by 7...a6. The current game shows White's modern way of playing
against this system. The first important crossroads arises after} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O a6 8. b3 {This is a
modern trend nowadays. The idea is to overprotect the important c4-pawn.} ({
The old main line goes} 8. d5 Na5 9. Nd2 c5 10. Qc2 Rb8 11. b3 b5 {when the
arising complicated positions provide Black with enough counterplay.}) 8... Rb8
{[%cal Gb7b5] Black prepares the thematic ...b7-b5. White's most precise
reaction is} 9. d5 Na5 ({After} 9... Nxd5 $2 10. cxd5 Bxc3 11. Bh6 Ne5 12. Bxf8
Bxa1 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qxa1 $16 {White enjoys a healthy extra pawn.}) 10. Bg5 {
White's best way of anticipating the advance ...c7-c5. The point of this move
will become clear a bit later.} c5 ({Clearly worse is} 10... b5 $6 {which is
well met by} 11. cxb5 axb5 12. b4 Nc4 13. Qb3 {[%csl Rb5,Rc6][%cal Gf3d4,Ga2a4]
Black's queenside is rather shaky. White is planning to follow with ideas such
as Nd4 and a2-a4.}) 11. dxc6 Nxc6 12. Rc1 {This is the typical pawn structure
White was going for. It is now obvious that besides freeing the c1-square for
the rook, the move 10.Bg5 contributes to the fight for the important d5-square.
Additionally, Black should always reckon with the pressure on the h4-d8
diagonal.} h6 {In order to chase the bishop away, Black accepts some kingside
weaknesses.} 13. Be3 Ng4 14. Bd2 Bd7 15. Nd5 {As pointed out in the preview of
the structure, installing a knight on d5 is White's most common idea. In the
long run, Black will either exchange the knight or chase it away by means of ..
.e7-e6. In the first case, White will recapture with a pawn (ideally exd5 if
the move e2-e4 has been played), thus enjoying a considerable space advantage.
In the game, Black went for the second option -} e6 16. Nc3 {The problem with
the move 15...e6 is the weakness of the d6-pawn. Adhiban exploited it in a
very instructive way. The game followed} Nce5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Ne4 {[%cal
Gd2b4] White is ready to put even more pressure on d6 by means of Bb4.
Therefore, Black is forced to accept an inferior version of IQP.} d5 19. cxd5
exd5 20. Nc5 Bc6 21. Bf4 {White's advantage is obvious. Black is doomed to
passivity. Later on, White managed to convert his advantage without much of a
trouble.} Qa5 22. a4 Rbd8 23. Qe1 Qb6 24. Bxe5 Bxe5 25. Nd3 Bg7 26. Qb4 Qc7 27.
Qf4 Qe7 28. Bf3 Rd6 29. Rc2 a5 30. Rc5 b6 31. Rc2 Bb7 32. Rfc1 Ba6 33. Rc7 Qe6
34. Qd2 Bxd3 35. Qxd3 Bb2 36. R1c2 Ba3 37. Kg2 Bb4 38. Qd4 Re8 39. e3 Qe5 40.
Rc8 Qe6 41. Bg4 f5 42. R2c7 Rd7 43. Bf3 Rxc8 44. Rxc8+ Kf7 45. Qh8 h5 46. Rg8
Qf6 47. Bxd5+ 1-0

