{We shall now examine an instructive game played by Alexander Grischuk.
Instead of going after the g5-bishop (as it was the case in the prevous
example), his opponent tried another typical idea - prepare the advance ...
b7-b5. It turns out, however, that this strategy can hardly resist against
White's central play.} 12... Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 13. Nd5 {White should play
this thematic move almost regardless of what Black is doing. Once again, we
can see the benefits of playing Bg5 earlier.} Ne4 14. Be3 b5 15. Nd4 $1 {
A classical approach to the position. The opponent's activity on the wing is
best answered with a blow in the centre. In this particular case, Grischuk
makes use of the unstable position of Black's knights.} Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17.
Qxd4 Nc5 18. b4 Ne6 19. Qh4 $1 {The queen is pretty annoying on h4.
Additionally, after the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, Black's king is
vulnerable. The next few moves are quite logical.} Re8 20. c5 dxc5 21. bxc5 Rc8
22. Qb4 a5 23. Qa3 Nd4 24. Qb2 e5 $2 {A serious mistake.} ({Black should have
played} 24... Ne6 {when after} 25. Rfd1 Nxc5 26. Qd4 {White still should prove
his compensation.}) 25. Nb6 Rxc5 $2 {This move loses by force.} ({The only way
to prolong the resistance was} 25... Bg4 26. f3 Rxc5 27. Rxc5 Qxb6 28. Rfc1 b4
{[%cal Gd4e6]} 29. Kh1 Be6 {Keeping at least some counterplay.}) 26. Nxd7 Rxc1
27. Rxc1 Qxd7 28. e3 Nf5 29. Bc6 Qe7 30. Bxe8 Qxe8 31. Rc5 1-0

