{This typical Benoni structure arises in the systems with ...Nc6 or ...c7-c5.
The plans for both sides are more or less clear. With his knight usually being
on a5, Black plays on the queenside. His normal play goes ...a7-a6 followed by
...Rb8 and ...b7-b5. Later on, under favourable circumstances, Black could
consider opening the queenside with ...bxc4. Just like in every Benoni
position, the queenside activity is well supported by the g7-bishop. On the
other hand, White's play is in the centre. His strategy is based on the
preparation of the advance e4-e5. Before proceeding with the central play,
however, White needs to neutralize the queenside pressure. For this purpose,
White usually makes the following moves - Qc2, b2-b3, Bb2 and Rb1. The last
move Rb1 is aimed at preventing possible exchange sacrifices on b2. Later on,
White can start preparing his central expansion. A typical way of doing so is
the manoeuvre Nc3-e2-c1-d3 (meanwhile the moves e2-e4 and e7-e5 are usually
played). The d3-square is the perfect spot for the white knight. From this
position, the knight controls the queenside and supports the advance e4-e5. My
conclusion is that if White knows what he is doing, at some point, Black would
run out of counterplay. I illustrate all these ideas with a game of mine.}  *

