{[%evp 0,61,19,31,54,67,59,30,37,-13,11,13,21,17,17,4,18,26,-2,-18,7,26,36,20,
6,10,44,14,15,-13,38,38,38,43,60,34,32,41,45,52,37,67,94,91,85,97,130,63,61,61,
92,115,113,138,108,92,154,115,188,163,176,173,185,178] Now, I would like to
show a game of mine which features a typical Benoni structure. The position of
interest arises after} 1. d4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O
Nc6 7. Nc3 Bf5 {[%cal Gf6e4] Quite a popular move. Black is planning to
exchange a pair of knights with ...Ne4, thus solving his spatial problems.
Therefore, White should play actively.} ({An interesting structure might arise
after the alternative bishop move} 7... Bg4 8. d5 Bxf3 ({After} 8... Na5 9. Nd2
c5 {We have a structure which is similar to the game.}) 9. exf3 Ne5 10. Qe2 c5
11. f4 Ned7 12. Bd2 $14 {This pawn structure is known to be favourable for
White. He enjoys a bishop pair and a space advantage. In the future, White
will combine the pressure along the e-file with kingside threats.}) 8. d5 Na5
9. Nd2 c5 10. e4 Bd7 11. Qc2 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] Preparing to connect the
rooks by means of b2-b3 followed by Bb2.} a6 12. b3 Rb8 13. Bb2 b5 14. Rab1 $1
{A very important prophylactic move which is typical for the pawn structure.
In general, White's long-term strategy is based on advance e4-e5. Nevertheless,
before proceeding with the main plan, I try to eliminate any possible
counterplay. White's last move anticipate any possible exchange sacrifices
after ...bxc4 bxc4.} Qc7 15. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Ge2c1,Gc1d3,Gf2f4,Ge4e5,Gd2e4]
Another important move that you should remember. The knight is heading to d3
which is the perfect square in this structure. Besides keeping the queenside
under control, the d3-knight would support the advance e4-e5 as well.} Rb7 $6 {
This is a pointless move since Black has no perspectives on the b-file.} ({
Better would have been to grab some space in the centre by playing} 15... e5 {
Even in this case, however, White's strategy would remain the same.}) 16. Bc3
Rd8 17. Rbe1 {[%cal Ge2c1,Gc1d3,Gf2f4,Ge4e5] Since the b-file is under control,
the rook would rather belong to the kingside. It's already very difficult for
Black to create counterplay.} bxc4 18. bxc4 Ng4 {Having less space, Black is
trying to provoke exchanges. On the other hand, the exchange of the
dark-squared bishops makes the black king vulnerable. The next moves are quite
logical.} 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qc3+ f6 21. h3 Nh6 22. Nc1 $1 e5 23. Nd3 Rbb8 {
This move practically admits the failure of the entire strategy.} 24. f4 Nb7
25. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5] White is ready to break on the kingside. The advance
g4-g5 is coming.} g5 26. fxg5 fxg5 27. Rf2 {[%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3] Another precise
move. White is preparing the manoeuvre Nd2-f1-g3, thus making use of the
opponent's kingside weaknesses. The game is over.} Re8 28. Nf1 Re7 29. Ng3 Nd8
30. Nh5+ Kg8 31. Ref1 1-0

