{Sometimes, this typical English structure can be reached in King's Indian
Defence. This happens when White releases the central tension by playing dxe5.
Statically speaking, due to his good central control, Black is doing pretty
much okay in this structure. Very often, however, White gains an advantage due
to the superior activity of the pieces. In many positions, in order to take
the d5-square under control, and restrict the g2-bishop, Black opts for the
advance ...c7-c6. This move, however, weakens the d6-square which can be used.
Another key element is the control of the d-file. Therefore, both sides are
fighting for it. My conclusion is that with a precise play, Black can
neutralize White's initiative.}  *

