{[#]} 7. dxe5 dxe5 {This exchange looks like a small concession, giving away
White's space advantage in the centre and clearing space for Black's pieces.
If played as in this game, with the intention of exchanging pieces and
reaching a draw, it is likely to lead to trouble. Before taking on e5, White
should be sure that he can get control over the d-file and use some other
weaknesses in Black's camp. If his initiative vanishes, Black will have
chances to exploit the weakness on d4.} 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bg5 Nbd7 10. Nd5 $2 {
Just premature.} (10. O-O-O Rf8 11. Nd5 c6 12. Ne7+ Kh8) 10... c6 11. Ne7+ Kf8
12. Nxc8 Rdxc8 13. O-O-O Nc5 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Bd3 a5 16. Rhe1 Re8 17. Bf1 Bd8
$1 {The best square for the bishop seems to be b6, from where it keeps the
f2-pawn under pressure, restricting the activity of White's rooks. However,
Kasparov had in mind a more ambitious job for the bishop, as we shall see soon.
} 18. g3 {The activation of the white bishop is by far less effective since
there is nothing to be attacked along the h3-c8 diagonal.***Knowing the future
course of events,} (18. b3 {suggests itself as an important alternative,
aiming to prevent ...a4. However, this move would only delay Black's plan,
leaving White's queenside with additional weaknesses at the same time after}
Bb6 19. g3 Re7 20. Bh3 Na6 21. Re2 a4 $1 $36 {and White's king starts feeling
insecure.}) 18... a4 19. Kc2 Ba5 20. Re3 $6 (20. Re2 {, maintaining the second
rank defended, was somewhat better. Black would probably defend his e5-pawn
with} f6 {before occupying the open file.}) 20... Rad8 $1 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Bh3
(22. Nxe5 Rd2+ 23. Kc1 Rxf2 24. Rf3 $1 Rxh2 $1 {The exchange of rooks would
increase the probability of a draw dramatically.} 25. Nxf7 (25. Rxf7+ Ke8 $17 {
, White's activity along the seventh rank would be sterile and transitory. In
fact, the rook should retreat immediately because of the threats ...Rh5 or ...
a3 followed by ...Bc3.}) 25... Ke7 $17 {, Black wouldn't retain the better
structure and more active pieces.}) 22... f6 23. Re2 Ke7 24. Bg2 Nd3 $1 {
Suddenly, there is a strong threat of ...NNb4+ and if KKb1?? (defending the
a2-pawn), then ...RRd1#!} 25. a3 {In the King's Indian, this "self-blocking
move", as Botvinnik called it, is rather controversial. From a static point of
view, it obviously favours Black, who is left with an eternal knight on c5.
However, the potential threat of ...a3 is quite irritating for White and it is
suggestive that Botvinnik himself played a2-a3 in a famous game he lost to
King's Indian specialist Geller. (see below) Here, White's decision is
justified by the fact that the only alternative way to parry the
aforementioned threat} (25. b3 a3 $1 26. Bh3 Nb4+ 27. Kc1 {(The fact that the
a2-pawn is defended by the rook is a feeble consolation)} Bb6 $19 {and the
f2-pawn is doomed. The merits of Danailov's move is that it allows White to
keep his king on c2, out of the enemy knight's range and practically
preventing the loss of the f2-pawn. However, the newly created weakness is
very harmful to White's position. So far, Black has been in total control of
the dark squares only, but getting an outpost on a light square (b3) will add
force to his attack.}) 25... Nc5 $1 {After having provoked the desired effect,
the knight returns to the base. We should notice that Black's minor pieces
create some sort of barrier (b3-c3-d3-d2) in front of White's forces. This
always happens when a knight and a bishop are placed on squares of the same
colour not far from each other. Black couldn't have won the f2-pawn with} (
25... Bb6 {, but this would have allowed the exchange of rooks after} 26. Rd2
Nxf2 27. Rxd8 Kxd8 $15 {, making the win quite problematic.}) 26. h4 h5 27. Re3
$6 {An entirely excusable inaccuracy, allowing Black to win by simple means.
White was so restricted in his actions that choosing from a couple of evils
was not at all easy. Here, he should not have weakened the defence of the
d2-square.} (27. Bh3 Rd6 $22 {offers Black the idea of playing for Zugzwang.}
28. Bc8 {(Aiming to restrict the black knight's activity, but placing the
bishop on a vulnerable square.)} (28. g4 $2 {would be strongly met by} Nd3 $1)
(28. Bg2 Nb3 {is similar to the main line.}) 28... Rd3 29. Re3 {(Otherwise ...
RRd4)} Rd8 $1 {(Winning an essential tempo after having decoyed the enemy rook
on a vulnerable square. The position looks promising after the exchange of
rooks on e3, but White could still hope).} 30. Bh3 Bb6 31. Re2 Nb3 32. g4 {
What else?} Na1+ $1 33. Kc1 (33. Kb1 $2 {leads to "helpmate" after} Rd1+ 34.
Ka2 Nb3) 33... Rd3 {We can notice the importance of getting the extra-tempo ...
BBb6 for free. White cannot defend his minor pieces anymore, for instance} 34.
Bg2 Nb3+ 35. Kc2 Rxf3 $1 $19) 27... g5 $1 {This strong move is enabled by the
unfortunate placement of the white rook. Soon, the furthermore advance of the
g-pawn will suffocate White.} 28. hxg5 fxg5 29. Re2 (29. Nxg5 {loses material
to} Bd2) (29. Nxe5 {leads to a decisive black attack after} Rd2+ 30. Kb1 (30.
Kc1 Rxf2 {leads to big material losses because of the threatened fork on d2.})
30... Bc7 31. Nf3 Rxf2 32. Ne1 Be5 $1 {An impressive position. The white king
is helpless against the combined attack of all Black's pieces.}) 29... Nb3 {
The threat ...g4 following by the fork on d4 forces the white king retreat to
a vulnerable position.} 30. Kb1 Kf6 $1 {Playing cat and mouse.} 31. Nh2 Rd1+
32. Kc2 Rg1 0-1

