{[#]} 10. Rd1 ({This is more consistent than} 10. Nd5 {, but not the most
challenging.}) (10. O-O-O {has the advantage of connecting rooks, resulting in
a small concrete difference.} Rf8 11. Nd5 c6 12. Ne7+ Kh8 13. Be3 Re8 14. Nxc8
Rexc8 15. g4 $1 {White has to maintain the rhythm of his micro-initiative, in
order to compensate for the weakness on d4.} Rc7 ({The generally desirable} 
15... Rd8 {is risky because White can double his rooks along the d-file
quicker than in the main line.} 16. Nd2 Bf8 17. g5 Ne8 18. Nb3 a5 19. a4 {
Planning to double rooks on the d-file.} Ng7 20. Bg4 f5 21. gxf6 Nxf6 22. Rxd8
Rxd8 23. Rd1 Rxd1+ 24. Bxd1 Bb4 25. Bb6 $18 {Black's queenside is doomed.}) 16.
Nd2 Bf8 17. g5 Ne8 18. Nb3 $5 $146 (18. Bg4 Bc5 {solves Black?s problems.} 19.
Bxd7 Bxe3 20. fxe3 Rxd7 21. Nf3 Re7 22. Rd3 Nc7 23. Rhd1 Kg7 24. Rd7 Rae8 25.
Nxe5 Ne6 26. Rxe7 Rxe7 27. Nf3 h6 {1/2-1/2 (53) Van Zyl Rudd,J (2041)-Frolov,A
(2389) Budapest 2017}) 18... a5 19. a4 (19. Bg4 a4 20. Bxd7 axb3 21. axb3 Nd6
22. Bg4 Nxe4 $11) 19... Ng7 20. Bg4 f5 21. gxf6 Nxf6 $11) 10... Rf8 11. Nd2 (
11. Nd5 {is less challenging than in the lines above.} c6 12. Ne7+ Kh8 13. Be3
Re8 14. Nxc8 Rexc8 15. g4 Rd8 $5) 11... c6 12. Be3 Re8 13. c5 {Fighting
against the blockade on dark squares.} Bf8 14. Nb3 $2 {Just misplacing the
knight.} (14. b4 {was necessary, even though Black equalises comfortably.} a5
15. a3 axb4 16. axb4 Ra3 17. Rc1 b6 $11) 14... a5 15. a4 Nb8 $1 {Black has all
the squares he needs for his minor pieces.} 16. Bc4 Na6 17. f3 Nd7 18. Bxa6
Rxa6 19. Kf2 f5 $17 20. exf5 gxf5 21. Rhe1 Kf7 22. f4 e4 23. g4 Nf6 24. gxf5
Bxf5 25. Bd4 e3+ 26. Bxe3 Bc2 0-1

