{[#]This game features an interesting struggle between White's sustained
initiative and Black's calm defence, based on maintaining the control over the
dark squares.} 8. Be3 Re8 9. dxe5 (9. d5 Nd4 $1 $10) 9... dxe5 10. Qxd8 Nxd8 {
Recycling the knight and planning ...c7-c6 followed by ...Ne6.} 11. Nb5 Ne6 12.
Ng5 Re7 13. Rfd1 (13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. f3 c6 15. Nc3 Rd7 16. Rfd1 Bf8 17. Kf2 b6
18. b3 Rb7 19. Na4 Nd7 20. Nb2 b5 $10 {Larsen, B-Fischer, R Santa Monica II.
Piatigorsky Cup 1966}) 13... b6 $1 {The safest move, restricting the activity
of White's pieces and consolidating the control over the dark squares at the
same time.} (13... c6 $5 {allows the undesired} 14. Nxa7 $5 {Larsen,B} (14.
Nxe6 Bxe6 15. Nc3 Rd7 $10 {Reshevsky, S-Fischer, R (9) Los Angeles 1961}) 14...
Bd7 (14... Nd4 15. Nxc8 Nxe2+ 16. Kf1 Rxc8 17. Kxe2 h6 18. Nf3 Nxe4 19. Nd2 Nd6
20. a4) 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. f3 Rd7 $1 $44 {/\ Rd4} 17. a4 Rd4 18. Rxd4 exd4 19.
Bxd4 Nd7 20. Be3 Bf8 21. a5 Bc5 22. Bxc5 Nxc5 23. Nxc6 bxc6 24. b4 {Marin}) 14.
c5 $5 {The only way of maintaining the initiative.} (14. Nxe6 Bxe6 15. f3 $10)
14... Nxc5 (14... bxc5 $2 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Bxc5 Rd7 17. f3 $18) 15. Rd8+ Bf8 (
15... Re8 16. Rxe8+ Nxe8 17. Bxc5 bxc5 18. Bc4 $1) (15... Ne8 $2 16. Bxc5 bxc5
17. Nxc7 Rxc7 18. Rxe8+ Bf8 19. Nxh7 $1) 16. Nxa7 Rxa7 $1 {Another example of
good judging. This exchange increases Black's chances for a blockade on dark
squares, while also keeping the white initiative under control.} (16... Bb7 17.
Rxa8 Bxa8 18. f3 $36 c6 19. Nc8 Rb7 20. Rd1) 17. Rxc8 Kg7 (17... Ncxe4 $4 18.
Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Bh6) (17... h6 $1 18. Nf3 Kg7 19. Bxc5 bxc5 20. Bd3 $10) 18. f3 (
18. Bxc5 {is premature yet.} bxc5 19. f3 Rd7 20. Bc4 h6 21. Nxf7 (21. Nh3 Rd4
22. b3 Nd7 23. Rd8 Be7 24. Re8 Bd6 25. Nf2 Nb6 $17) 21... Rxf7 22. Bxf7 Kxf7
23. a4 Ng8 24. a5 Ne7 25. Rb8 Nc6 26. Rb5 Ra6 $17 {Marin}) 18... Ne8 19. a3 {
This should have led to a quick draw by repetition.} (19. Bxc5 $1 {was the
only way to continue playing in a position with mutual chances.} bxc5 20. Rb8
$14 {Larsen.} (20. a4 h6 21. Nh3 Nd6 22. Rb8 Nb7 23. Rd1 Re6 24. Nf2 Rb6 25.
Rd7 Rxa4 26. Rxc7 Rxb2 27. Bf1 Rab4 28. Nd3 Bd6 29. Nxb4 Na5) 20... c6 (20...
Nd6 21. Nxh7) (20... h6 21. Nh3 Nd6 22. Nf2 Re6 23. a4 Nb7) 21. a4 Rab7 22.
Rxb7 Rxb7 23. Ra2 (23. a5 Rxb2 24. Bc4 Nd6 25. Bxf7 Be7 26. a6 Nc8 27. Be6 Nb6
28. h4 c4 29. Bxc4 Nxc4 30. a7 Nb6 31. a8=Q Nxa8 32. Rxa8 Rb1+ 33. Kh2 h6 34.
Ne6+ Kf7 35. Nd8+ Bxd8 36. Rxd8 Rc1 $11) 23... Rb4 24. a5 c4 25. g3 (25. a6 c3)
25... Bc5+ 26. Kg2 Bd4 27. a6 h6 28. Nh3 Nc7 29. Nf2 (29. a7 Rxb2) 29... Nxa6
30. Rxa6 Rxb2 31. Kf1 Rb1+ 32. Nd1 c3 33. Rxc6 Rc1 34. Kg2 Rc2 $11 {Marin})
19... Nd6 20. Rd8 $6 {So far, attack and defence have been at the same level,
but Larsen pushes things a bit too far already.} (20. Rb8 {might have resulted
into a draw by repetition.} Nd7 21. Rd8 Nb7 22. Rc8 Nd6 $10) 20... h6 21. Nh3
Ne6 22. Rb8 Re8 23. Rxe8 Nxe8 {It may be too early to talk about Black's
advantage, but the tendency clearly is to his favour. After the exchange of
the dark-squared bishops, he will get excellent squares for his knights.} 24.
Bb5 (24. Nf2 $142 Bc5) (24. b4 $2 Bxb4) 24... Nd6 25. Bf1 Nb7 $1 26. Nf2 Bc5 $1
27. Bxc5 Nbxc5 28. Rd1 h5 $1 (28... Nd4 $2 29. Ng4 f6 30. f4 $1) 29. Rd5 (29.
Nd3 Nxd3 30. Bxd3 Nd4 31. Kf2 $17) 29... Kf6 30. h4 Ke7 $1 31. Bc4 (31. Rxe5 $2
c6 $19 {/\ Nd7; f7-f6}) 31... c6 32. Rd2 Nd4 33. Kf1 (33. Nd3 $142) 33... f5 $1
34. b4 (34. Nd3 $142) (34. exf5 Nxf5 {/\ Ne3+, Nxh4} 35. Re2 $2 Ng3+) 34... b5
$1 (34... Nd7 {Marin}) 35. Bg8 (35. bxc5 bxc4 $19) (35. Bxb5 $2 Ncb3 $19) 35...
fxe4 $1 36. fxe4 (36. bxc5 e3 37. Rxd4 (37. Rd3 exf2 38. Kxf2 Ra8 39. Ba2 b4) (
37. Ra2 $2 exf2 38. Kxf2 Kf8 $1) 37... exd4 38. Nd3 Rxa3 39. Ke2 Rc3) 36... Nd7
