{[#]In my database on Kortschnoj, I have examined his very instructive win
over Penrose, featuring our thematic structure after dxe5. I will only give a
short fragment of that game, later in the database, for the purpose of
comparison, as Kortschnoj was a true specialist of this structure and there
are few other excellent examples. As the next examples will show, his
manoeuvres in this type of positions proved lethal against KI specialists of
newer generations, too. What we should retain from all these games is that
dxe5 can be effective if Black weakens his queenside somehow. Penrose played ..
.b7-b5 followed by ...a7-a6. In the newer games ...a7-a6 will suffice.} 10. Kb1
{Clearing the c1-square for the knight.} a6 11. dxe5 $1 {After Black's last
move, the exchange is possible and more or less necessary.} (11. Nc1 {takes
the knight away from d4.} exd4 $1 12. Bxd4 (12. Rxd4 Nc5 13. Qc2 Rd8) 12... b5
{With the knight on d4 this would not work, of course.}) (11. g4 b5 (11... exd4
12. Nxd4 Re8 13. h4 {yields attacking chances.}) 12. d5 {with undesired
complications.} (12. dxe5 $2 Nxe5 $19)) 11... dxe5 {Forced.} ({With the
b6-square weak,} 11... Nxe5 $2 {loses the queen to} 12. Bb6) (11... Qxe5 12.
Bf4 {[%csl Gd6] is also bad.}) 12. Nc1 {Planning Qc2, Nb3, c4-c5, Na4. Those
wondering what the queen was doing on b3 in the Saemisch attack may be
surprised that Kortschnoj followed the model of a couple of games from the
'50s. His last move is an improvement over them, actually.} ({Both games went} 
12. Qa4 Qxa4 $6 {The queen exchange tends to favour White, as the black queen
can help to keep Black's position together while still underdeveloped.} (12...
Qc7 $1 {is better, leaving the white queen misplaced on a4.} 13. c5 Re8 14. Nc1
Nf8 15. Nb3 Be6 16. Qa5 Qe7 {Black has regrouped properly and has a viable
position.}) 13. Nxa4 b5 14. Nac3 Re8 15. Nc1 Bb7 (15... Nf8 16. Nb3 N6d7 17.
Rd6 {Benko,P-Haag,E Budapest 1956 (1-0, 46)}) 16. Nb3 Rad8 17. a4 (17. Be2)
17... bxa4 (17... b4 18. Na2 c5 19. Nac1 Bf8 20. Be2 Bc6 21. Na5 Ba8 22. g4)
18. Nxa4 Nf8 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. Bb6 Re8 21. Be2 Ne6 22. Rd1 {Aronin, L-Suetin,
A Riga 1954 (1-0, 83)}) 12... b5 {If Black plays in the same way as in the
recommended line above, White will be a tempo up, resulting into a decisive
difference.} (12... Re8 13. Qc2 Nf8 14. Nb3 Qc7 15. Na4 Ne6 {This does not do
much for the development, but Black needs to defend c5 in order to ensure some
safety to the queen.} ({Black misses a tempo to reach the regrouping} 15... Be6
{followed by ...Nfd7:} 16. Bb6 Qb8 17. c5 N6d7 18. Na5 {Black is paralysed.})
16. c5 {with a stable advance in development and advantage of space.} (16. Bb6
$6 Qe7)) 13. Qc2 Re8 (13... b4 14. Qa4 Qxa4 15. Nxa4 $16 {followed by Nb3,
with excellent control over the queenside.}) 14. Nb3 Qd8 (14... Qc7 15. cxb5
cxb5 16. g4 Nb6 17. Rc1 Be6 18. Qf2 Nc4 19. Bxc4 bxc4 20. Nc5 $16) 15. Be2 (15.
g4 $5 Qe7 16. h4 h5 17. g5 Nh7 18. Na5) 15... Rb8 16. Rd2 Bf8 17. Rhd1 {
White has achieved a perfect regrouping, while Black is struggling to complete
his development. The game is more or less decided.} bxc4 {Desperation.} 18.
Bxc4 Qc7 19. Na4 Rb4 20. Nc1 $1 {One may wish to remember all the knight
manoeuvres from Kortschnoj's games with this structure.} Kg7 21. Nd3 Rb8 22.
Bb3 Rb5 23. Rc1 c5 24. Naxc5 Nxc5 25. Nxc5 Qa5 26. Rd3 Re7 {This loses
material but there was not much to hope for anyway.} 27. Bd2 Qb6 (27... Qc7 28.
Ne6+ $5 {Not really the only winning move.}) 28. Na4 1-0

