{[#]We can notice that this time the queen stands where it is supposed to
stand. However, Kortschnoj will not use it for launching a king side attack
with Bh6, preperring to simplify to a very promising ending.} 10. Kb1 a6 {
The familiar invitation to an exchange on e5. But first things first, White
exchanges the queens.} 11. Nd5 $1 Qxd2 (11... Qd8 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 (12... Nxf6 $2
13. dxe5 $18) 13. h4 $16 {with a promsiing kingside attack.}) 12. Ne7+ Kh8 13.
Rxd2 Nb6 (13... exd4 $5 14. Rxd4 Ne8 $16 {is unappealing, but somehwat safer.})
(13... Re8 14. Nxc8 Raxc8 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. g3 Nc5 17. Bh3 Rb8 18. Rhd1 a5 19.
Rd6 $18) 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. c5 (15. Nxc8 Raxc8 16. Nc1 {may be more restrictive.
} Rfd8 17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. c5 Nbd7 19. Nb3 $18 {with similar domination as in
the game.}) 15... Nbd7 $6 (15... Na4 {would have offered better practical
chances, even though Black would be much worse anyway.} 16. Rc2 (16. Nxc8 {
is helping Black clearing the f8-square for the bishop.} Rfxc8 $1 17. Be3 Bf8
18. Rc2 Nd7) 16... Be6 17. b3 Rfd8 (17... Rfe8 18. Nxg6+ hxg6 19. bxa4 Rad8 20.
Rb2 Rd1+ 21. Kc2 Ra1 22. Nc3 Re7 23. Be3 $16 {followed by Rb1 or Rg1 and Be2.})
18. Nc1 Rd7 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. bxa4 $16) 16. Be3 Re8 17. Nxc8 Raxc8 18. Nc1 Bf8
19. Nb3 {The game is basically over.} Kg7 (19... a5 20. a4 {only adds a new
weakness in Black's camp.}) 20. g3 {The typical way to develop the bishop
after the exchange on c8.} Rc7 21. Bh3 Be7 22. Rhd1 {Once again, White has
reached a perfect regrouping.} Nf8 23. Na5 {Just threatening to win the
e5-pawn.} Ne6 (23... h5 24. Nc4 $18) (23... Ng8 {would keep the pawn, but
hardly save the game.} 24. Nc4 f6 (24... Bf6 25. Rd3 {[%cal Ge3d2,Gd2a5,Gd2c3]
planning Bd2-a5-c3.} Ne6 26. Rd7 $18) 25. f4 $18 {with a crushing advantage.})
24. Bxe6 fxe6 25. Nc4 1-0

