{[#]In order to find an opponent who could more or less hold his own in this
structure against Kortschnoj, we have to resort to a game from the far past.} 
9... a6 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. c5 Qe7 12. Na4 Rd8 13. Qc2 Nf8 14. Nb6 Rb8 15. Nc4 {
Maybe a bit premature, but White does not seem to have an advantage at this
stage anyway.} (15. O-O Be6 (15... Ne6 16. Rad1 Nd7 17. Na4 $16 {leaves Black
underdeveloped.}) 16. b4 (16. Rad1 N6d7 {prevents Nc4.}) 16... N6d7 17. Nc4
Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Ne6 19. h4 a5 20. a3 b5 $11 21. cxb6 axb4 22. axb4 Nxb6 $11)
15... Ne8 $6 {This yields White some advantage. There was no need to defend d6.
However, the knight retreat also plans a long meaningful regrouping.} (15...
Be6 $1 {is similar to the line above.} 16. Nd6 $6 b6 $15 17. b4 $2 a5 18. a3
bxc5 19. bxc5 Bb3 20. Qc3 a4 21. O-O Ne6 $19) 16. b4 Be6 17. O-O Bxc4 18. Qxc4
Ne6 19. h4 N8c7 20. Rad1 (20. a4 a5 21. bxa5 (21. b5 Nd4) 21... Na6) 20... Nb5
{All Black's minor pieces sustain the invasion on d4, but this does not solve
all his problems yet.} 21. a4 Nbd4 22. Bxd4 {White is heading for a position
with opposite-coloured bishops, where the blockade on d3 would offer him
better chances. The plan is correct, but the exchange is premature.} (22. a5 $1
{planning the same operation was better.} Nxe2+ 23. Qxe2 Nd4 24. Bxd4 Rxd4 25.
Rxd4 exd4 26. Qd3 {Everything is ready for the pawn attack.} h6 {The same plan
as in the game does not work out so well here.} 27. Re1 g5 $6 28. hxg5 hxg5 29.
e5 $1 $16) 22... Nxd4 (22... exd4 $5 23. Nc1 d3 $1 {Everything against the
blockade.} (23... a5 24. Nd3 $1 $16) 24. Rxd3 a5 $11) 23. Nxd4 Rxd4 $6 (23...
exd4 $1 {was the right way of fighting against the blockade.} 24. a5 (24. Rd3
b5 {offers Black counterplay against the b4-pawn, for instance} 25. axb5 Rxb5)
24... d3 $1 25. Rxd3 Rxd3 26. Qxd3 Rd8 {with enough compensation for the pawn.
Black is very active and White's queenside pawn may be vulnerable.}) 24. Rxd4
exd4 25. a5 Rd8 (25... d3 {loses a pawn without compensation after} 26. Rd1 {
as White keeps the control over the d-file.}) 26. Rd1 {I assume that both
players were in time trouble at this height, explaining a series of mutual
inaccuracies.} (26. Qd3 $1 h6 27. Bh3 Re8 28. Re1 Qd8 (28... f5 $2 29. e5 $1)
29. Re2 g5 30. h5 Be5 31. Rd2 Qf6 32. Qe2 {[%cal Gd2d3] followed by Rd3-f3
with constant pressure.}) 26... h6 $1 {Black has to fight against the enemy
pawn mass before it gets into motion.} 27. Qc2 Qd7 $5 (27... g5 28. hxg5 hxg5
29. Bh3 $5) 28. Bf1 g5 29. hxg5 hxg5 30. Bc4 {We can see that Kortschnoj had a
clear regrouping in mind.} Re8 (30... Qg4 $5 31. Kg2 d3 32. Bxd3 Rd4 $11) (
30... Be5 $5 31. Qe2 Kg7 32. Qh5 f6 $11) 31. Kg2 Qe7 (31... g4 32. Rh1 {
endangers the g4-pawn.}) 32. Re1 Qe5 (32... g4 33. e5 $1 $18) 33. Qb3 (33. Qe2
$16 {[%cal Ge2h5] followed by Qh5.}) 33... Qf6 34. Qd3 (34. Qd1 Qg6 35. Qg4 $16
) 34... Qg6 $11 35. Qe2 g4 36. Bd3 Re5 37. Rh1 Bf6 $6 (37... Rh5 $1 38. Rxh5
Qxh5 39. Bc2 Kf8 40. Bd1 Ke7 41. Qxg4 Qxg4 42. Bxg4 d3 43. Kf1 Kd8 44. Bh5 Ke7
$11) 38. Qd2 Qg7 39. Qb2 (39. Qf4 {followed by the king's evacuation would
have maintained a stable advantage.} Qg5 (39... Qg6 40. Rh6) 40. Kf1 Kg7 41.
Ke2 Re8 42. Kd2 (42. Kd1 Qg6 $5) 42... Re5 (42... Qg6 43. e5) 43. Kc2 Re8 44.
Rh2 Re5 45. Qxg5+ Bxg5 46. Rh5 f6 47. Kd1 Kg8 48. Be2 Rxe4 49. Bd3 Re7 50. Bf5
$18) 39... Re8 40. Rh5 Re5 41. Rxe5 Bxe5 42. Qe2 Qg5 43. Qd1 Qg6 1/2-1/2

