{[#]We will now start investigating the structures resulting after ...exd4.
Black's main idea is to make the c5-square available for his knight and clear
the long diagonal for his bishop. On the other hand, Black offers White even
more space and his d6-pawn may become weak. I have been fascinated by this
structure (from Black's point of view) ever since I have read Bronstein's book
Zuerich 53. However, in tournament games, I have been very effective with...
White. The general feeling is that Black is sort of bluffing, in the hope that
a moment will arrive when he will be able to deliver a tactical trick. We will
examine the typical ideas gradually, following the way they developed over the
decades. One of the first things I learned is that White should not develop
his bishop to b2. And yet, in some games, I did it for no reason and was lucky
not to be punished.} 11. Bb2 {I have input this game from memory, many years
after it was played. It might have been a bit different, but the small
combination below was the same.} exd4 12. Nxd4 Nc5 13. Re1 Nfd7 14. Re2 Ne5 15.
Rd2 {With the bishop on e3, White would have a clear advantage, but here he is
in trouble.} Bd7 $2 (15... Ncd3 $6 16. Na4 Nxb2 17. Nxb6 Nxd1 18. Nxa8 Nc3 19.
Re1 {[%cal Gf2f4]} (19. Rc1 Nxc4 20. bxc4 Bxd4) 19... g5 20. Re3 Nb1 21. Rd1
Na3 22. f4 $36 {[%csl Ga3]}) (15... Ned3 $1 16. Rxd3 (16. Nde2 Nxf2 17. Kxf2
Nd3+ 18. Kf3 Qf2#) 16... Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Qxd4 $17 {The bishop is useless on b2.})
16. Nce2 {... 1-0} *

