{[#]This and the next game are more consistent illustrations of the fact that
the bishop does not belong to b2.} 14... a4 {This works because the bishop
prevents b3-b4. Besides, the pawn on b3 is hanging now.} 15. Ba1 {As we will
see, the bishop is not safer on this square, either.} axb3 16. axb3 Ng4 17. h3
Rxa1 $1 {A typical combination, taking full advantage of White's vulnerability
on dark squares.} (17... Nxf2 $6 18. Na4 $1 (18. Qxf2 Rxa1) 18... Nxa4 19. bxa4
{[%csl Gb6]} Nxh3+ 20. Bxh3 Qc5 21. Bxc8 Rxa4 22. Bd7 Rd8 (22... Re7 23. Rxb7)
23. Bh3 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Bxd4+ 25. Kh2 Bxa1 26. Rxa1 Re8 {offers Black only
drawing chances.}) 18. Rxa1 Nxf2 $1 19. Re3 (19. Kxf2 Nxb3 $19) (19. Qxf2 Nd3)
19... Nxh3+ $19 {Black has two pawns for the exchange and a continuing attack.}
20. Kh2 (20. Bxh3 Bxh3 21. Kh2 {[%cal Gb6g1]} Bg4 {[%cal Gg7h6,Rg7a1,Re3d2,
Rb6f2] White is hopless against the numerous threats from all sides. For
instance:} 22. Ree1 Ne6 23. Nxe6 Bxc3 24. Qxc3 Qf2+ 25. Kh1 Bf3+) 20... Nf2 21.
Rf3 Ncxe4 22. Qf4 (22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Qf4 f5 {[%csl Rd4] is equally hopeless.})
22... Ng4+ 23. Kh1 f5 24. Nxe4 Rxe4 25. Qxd6 Rxd4 26. Qb8 Rd8 27. Ra8 Be5 28.
Qa7 Qb4 29. Qa2 Qf8 30. Bh3 Qh6 0-1

