{This game is a perfect illustration for the way Black is gambling in this
structure.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7.
O-O e5 8. e4 exd4 9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. f3 (10. h3 Re8 11. Re1 {is the main line.})
10... Nfd7 {With the development far from complete, this manoeuvre is
premature.} 11. Be3 c6 12. Qd2 a5 13. Rad1 Ne5 14. b3 a4 15. Nde2 $2 {Another
rule I learned from Bronstein's book is that the weakness on d6 is relative.
In order to attack the pawn, White has to retreat with his central knight. But
the knight is optimally placed precisely on d4! Jumping away usually offers
Black tactical ideas. In this case, b3 is left undefended.} (15. f4 $1 {
would have maintained White's advantage.} axb3 (15... Ned3 16. Nxa4 Nxa4 17.
bxa4 Nc5 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Bxc5 Bg4 20. Bxd6 Bxd1 21. Qxd1 Re8 22. e5 $16) (
15... Ng4 16. Nxc6 Nxb3 17. axb3 bxc6 18. Nxa4 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 Qe7 20. Nc3) 16.
fxe5 bxa2 17. Nxa2 {is the simplest} (17. exd6 Bg4 18. Ra1 Qxd6 19. Rxa2 Rxa2
$1 (19... Rad8 {Geller} 20. Nf3) 20. Nxa2 Rd8 21. Nf3 Nxe4 $44 {/+/=}) (17.
Nxc6 bxc6 18. Bxc5 Bg4 $17 {Geller}) 17... Bxe5 {Geller assesses the position
as "interesting" but Black's compensation for the piece looks questionable.
True, White would have a hard job-winning, but the fight would be one-sided.})
15... axb3 $3 (15... Be6 16. Qxd6 $2 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 axb3 18. Bxc5 bxa2 19. Ra1
Bxc4 $17) (15... Qa5 16. Qxd6 Ned7 17. Rb1 axb3 18. axb3 Bxc3 19. Nxc3 Qxc3 20.
Bxc5 Nxc5 21. Qxc5 Ra2 $44) (15... Qe7 16. f4 Ng4 (16... Ned3 17. Nxa4) 17.
Bxc5 dxc5 18. Nxa4) (15... Nxb3 16. axb3 axb3 {[%csl Gc4]} 17. c5 Nc4 $11 18.
Qd3 (18. Qc1 b2 $19 {[%csl Ge3]}) 18... Nb2 19. Qb1 $6 (19. Qd2 Nc4 $11) 19...
Nxd1 20. Rxd1 Qa5 21. cxd6 (21. Qxb3 Be6 22. Qb2 dxc5 $36) 21... Bxc3 22. Nxc3
Qxc3 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gd6d7]}) 16. Bxc5 Nxc4 17. Qc1 {Black has overwhelming
compensation for the piece, as his queenside pawns are very dangerous.} bxa2 $6
{This is strong enough, but not lethal yet.} (17... b2 $1 {would have more or
less won.} 18. Qc2 dxc5 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 {Black has only a rook and two pawns for
the queen, but White has unsolvable problems.} 20. Rd1 Be6 {Planning to
advance the b-pawn.} 21. f4 (21. a4 b5 22. axb5 cxb5 23. Nxb5 Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1
Ra1) 21... Bd4+ 22. Nxd4 cxd4 23. Nb1 Ne3 24. Qd2 Nxd1 25. Qxd1 Bxa2 26. Kf2 d3
27. e5 Bxb1 28. Qxb1 d2 29. Bf3 d1=Q 30. Bxd1 Rd2+ 31. Ke3 Ra1) 18. Nxa2 Qa5
19. Qxc4 Be6 (19... b5 $5 {might have been more useful.} 20. Qc2 (20. Qb4 dxc5
21. Qxa5 Rxa5 22. Nac1 c4) 20... dxc5) 20. Qc1 dxc5 21. Nac3 b5 {The strong
pawn mass sustained by the bishops is threatening, ensuring Black fantastic
compensation.} (21... Bb3 $5) 22. Nb1 (22. f4 {Geller} b4 23. f5 Bc4 24. f6 Bh8
25. Rf4 bxc3 $17) ({White could have used Black's wasted tempo ...Be6 with} 22.
e5 $5 Bxe5 23. f4 Bg7 24. Bxc6 {mudding up the waters.}) 22... b4 23. Nf4 Bb3
24. Rd6 c4 25. Rxc6 c3 $17 {Caging the b1-knight.} 26. Nd5 Bxd5 27. exd5 Qxd5
28. f4 Qd4+ 29. Kh1 Ra2 30. Bf3 Rb2 31. f5 Be5 32. Qe1 Rd8 33. Be4 Kg7 34. f6+
Kg8 35. Ra6 h5 36. Ra5 h4 37. Bxg6 Rxh2+ 38. Kxh2 Bxg3+ 39. Qxg3 hxg3+ 40. Kh3
fxg6 0-1

