{[#]SHortly before the Zurich 53 Candidates' tournament, where this structure
was very popular, Najdorf played a game featuring the same aspects as revealed
there.} 8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8 10. Re1 c6 11. h3 a5 12. Be3 Nc5 13. Qc2 a4 14.
Rad1 Nfd7 15. f4 Qa5 16. Bf2 {One of the elements making this variation
appealing for the players with black is the queenside domination and relative
stability on dark squares. However, White can usually maintain control by
simple means. The only problems might arise when White tries to generate an
active plan, as pawn expansion is not without risk.} Qb4 17. a3 (17. Nb1 $5) (
17. Bf1 $6) 17... Qa5 (17... Qxc4 $2 18. Bf1 $18) 18. Nb1 {One of the reasons
why Black won this game and the next few ones in this database is that White
shied away from advancing his kingside pawns. Optically, this looks
double-edged, but it is more consistent than the plans actually played.} (18.
g4 $1 {was played in a more recent game.} Nb6 19. Bf1 Ne6 {This could have led
to trouble.} 20. Qd2 (20. e5 $1 dxe5 21. b4 axb3 22. Nxb3 Qa7 23. f5 {The pin
of the b6-knight is very unpleasant.}) 20... Nc5 21. Qc2 Be6 {Black does not
repeat the moves, avoiding the previous line. But this move should not solve
his problems, either.} 22. Nb1 $1 (22. Nxe6 $2 {Jojua,D (2588)-Ehlvest,J (2521)
chess.com INT 2019 (0-1, 40)} Rxe6 $1 $11 {offers Black easy play.}) 22... Rad8
23. Nd2 Bc8 24. e5 $1 Nbd7 (24... dxe5 25. b4 $1) 25. exd6 Bf8 26. b4 axb3 27.
N4xb3 {Black will have a hard time retrieving the pawn and his queen does not
find comfort easily.}) 18... Nf6 19. Nd2 Bd7 20. Re2 (20. g4 $5 {planning
Nf1-g3 is still strong. In such situations, White may instinctively fear} Bxg4
$5 (20... h6 21. Nf1) 21. hxg4 Nxg4 {but things are less dangerous than they
look.} 22. Nf1 (22. b4 axb3 23. N2xb3 Nxb3 24. Nxb3 Qxa3 {is reasonable for
Black.}) 22... Nxf2 23. Qxf2 f5 24. Ng3 fxe4 25. Bxe4 $5 {Black has certain
practical chances, but hardly full compensation for the piece, as White is
well regrouped.}) 20... Re7 21. Rde1 Rae8 {Black only needed these few tempi
of White's hesitation to complete his development in an optimal way. The
situation has turned less clear already.} 22. Nf1 $6 (22. g4 {was still
necessary.} h6 $5 {is probably best. The position may be statically and
dynamically balanced, as none of the players has clear ways of making progress.
For instance,} (22... Bxg4 {may be a bit premature yet. The following line is
interesting but probably not satisfactory for Black.} 23. hxg4 Nxg4 24. b4 Qa7
(24... axb3 25. N4xb3 Nxb3 26. Nxb3 Qxa3 27. Bh4 $16) 25. bxc5 Nxf2 26. cxd6
Bxd4 27. Kf1 Ng4 28. Nf3 Ne3+ 29. Rxe3 Bxe3 30. dxe7 Bxf4 31. e5 {After taking
on e7 Black will have enough pawns for the piece. However, Qe4-h4 is likely to
create unpleasant kingside threats.}) 23. Nf1 {takes the knight away from the
queenside, allowing} Bxg4 $1 {under improved circumstances.} 24. hxg4 Nxg4 {
One important point is that the knight on d4 is not defended by the rook
anymore.} 25. b4 {Less effective than above, but necessary in order to avoid
the worst.} axb3 26. Nxb3 Nxb3 27. Qxb3 Nxf2 28. Kxf2 Bd4+ 29. Kg3 g5 {with
entirely adequate compensation for the piece.}) 22... h5 $1 $15 {White can
forget about g3-g4 already.} 23. Nh2 Bc8 24. Nf1 Bh6 (24... h4 $1 {would have
been even stronger.} 25. g4 (25. gxh4 Nh5 $17) 25... Bxg4 $1 26. hxg4 Nxg4 27.
Nf3 ({With the black pawn on h4, the saving line} 27. b4 axb3 28. Nxb3 Nxb3 29.
Qxb3 Nxf2 30. Kxf2 {does not work any more, as after} Bd4+ {the king cannot go
to g3. Advancing to f3 allows mate in one with ...Qh5, while} 31. Ne3 Qh5 $19
32. Bf3 Qh6 $19) 27... Nxf2 28. Kxf2 (28. Rxf2 Nxe4 29. Rfe2 Qf5 $17) 28... Ne6
{One of the few promising continuations.} (28... Bxb2 29. Nxh4 Bxa3) (28... Qb6
29. Nxh4 Nd3+ 30. Kg3) 29. Nxh4 (29. c5 Qxc5+ 30. Qxc5 Nxc5 31. Kg1 Nd3 32. Rd1
Nxf4) 29... Nxf4 30. Rd2 Qg5 {with a clear black advantage in all the cases.})
25. f5 {A clear concession but White did not have anything better.} (25. h4 Ng4
$19) 25... Kh7 26. Nh2 Qc7 27. h4 Qa5 28. fxg6+ fxg6 $17 29. Ndf3 Nb3 30. Be3
Bg7 31. Ng5+ Kg8 32. Bf3 Nd7 33. Kh1 Ne5 34. Bg2 Qa6 35. Bf4 Nd4 36. Qd1 Nxe2
37. Rxe2 Qxc4 38. Bf1 Qb3 39. Rc2 Kh8 40. Bxe5 Bxe5 41. Bc4 Qxg3 42. Rg2 Qxh4
43. Ngf3 Qf6 44. Ng5 d5 45. Be2 Bf4 46. Qg1 Bxg5 47. Rxg5 Bg4 0-1

