{[#]This is probably the most famous game with this structure. It was played
by the official author of Zuerich 53 (the de facto author seems to have been
Weinstein), and Bronstein knew how to add drama when mentioning that Reshevsky
offered a draw twice. This seems to be questionable, as, in the later book
written together with Tom Fuerstenberg, The Sorcerer's apprentice, Bronstein
praises his opponent for his high fighting spirit and does not mention any
draw offer. Well, this is how Bronstein was... but this does not take away
merit from his as a player. And the game IS very interesting, indeed.} 15. Nde2
{We are familiar with the fact that this knight retreat is ineffective..
However, this will not influence the battle, as both White and Black will have
to waste two tempi.} Qa5 $1 16. Bf1 Ne5 17. Nd4 a3 $5 {Bronstein chooses a
setup based on two outposts on dark squares.} 18. f4 Ned7 19. b3 Na6 $1 20. Bf2
Ndc5 21. Re3 Nb4 22. Qe2 {"The game is probably positionally lost for White "
(U. Andersson). Marin: this sounds like an overstatement, but it would be more
accurate to say that it radically contradicts the truth. Black has a beautiful
position but there is no obvious way of making progress if White patiently
marks time with neutral moves. In fact, White has a stable advantage.} Bd7 {
/\Re8-e7, Ra8-e8} 23. e5 $6 {Marin: White does what Black was dreaming of
doing, opening the centre. From now on, the queenside pressure will become
real, as White has created worries in the centre for himself.} (23. g4 $1 {
Since there are no sacrifices on g4 available, it is hard to explain why
Reshevsky refrained from this plan.} Re7 (23... Bxd4 24. Rxd4 Ne6 25. Rxd6 Nxf4
26. Qf3 $18 {Najdorf}) 24. Bh4 f6 {Marin. Black's position remains hard to
break, but White cannot really complain.}) (23. Bg2 $5 Re7 24. g4 $1 Rae8 $6
25. Bh4 f6 $14 {Marin}) 23... dxe5 24. fxe5 Rad8 {Black is perfectly mobilised
and able to exploit the numerous white weaknesses.} 25. g4 Ne6 26. Bh4 Nxd4 27.
Rxd4 Qc5 28. Rde4 (28. Rd1 Rxe5 $1) 28... Bh6 $1 29. Kh1 Be6 (29... Bxe3 30.
Rxe3 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gc3e4,Ge4f6] Najdorf}) 30. g5 (30. Bxd8 Rxd8 31. Rg3 Rd2
32. Qe1 Nxa2 $19) (30. Bf6 Bxe3 31. Rxe3 Qd4 $1) 30... Bg7 31. Rf4 Bf5 32. Ne4
Bxe4+ $1 (32... Qxe5 $2 33. Rxf5 $1 (33. Nf6+ Bxf6 34. Rxe5 Rxe5 35. Qf2 Be7
$17 {Marin}) 33... gxf5 (33... Qxf5 34. Nf6+ Bxf6 35. Rxe8+ Rxe8 36. Qxe8+ Kg7
37. gxf6+ $18) 34. Nf6+ Bxf6 35. gxf6 $1 Qxe3 36. Qg2+ $18) 33. Rfxe4 Na6 $1 {
/\Na6-c7-e6} 34. e6 fxe6 35. Rxe6 Rf8 36. Re7 Bd4 37. R3e6 Qf5 $1 38. Re8 (38.
Bg2 Nc5 $19) 38... Nc5 39. Rxd8 Nxe6 40. Rxf8+ Kxf8 $1 $17 41. Bg3 Qxg5 (41...
Nxg5 42. Bd6+ Kg7 43. Qe7+ $10) 42. Qxe6 Qxg3 43. Qc8+ Ke7 44. Qg4 (44. Qxb7+
$2 Kd8 45. Qa8+ Kc7 46. Qa5+ Bb6 $19 47. Qd2 Qg1#) 44... Qc3 45. Kg2 Qb2+ 46.
Qe2+ Kd6 47. Kf3 (47. Qxb2 axb2 48. Bd3 Ke5 49. Kf3 Bc5 50. Bb1 Kf6 51. Ke4 h5
52. Bc2 g5 53. Bb1 Bd6 54. Bc2 g4 55. hxg4 hxg4 56. Bb1 g3 57. Kf3 Bf4 $19 {
/\Kf6-c1 Euwe.}) 47... Bc5 48. Ke4 Qd4+ 49. Kf3 Qf6+ 50. Kg2 Kc7 51. Qf3 Qb2+
52. Qe2 Qd4 53. Kf3 h5 54. Kg2 g5 55. Kg3 Qf4+ 56. Kg2 g4 57. hxg4 hxg4 58. Kh1
Kb6 59. Kg2 Kc7 60. Kh1 Bd6 61. Kg1 Kb6 62. Qg2 Bc5+ 63. Kh1 Qh6+ 64. Qh2 Qe3
65. b4 Bd4 $138 {Zugzwang. White lost on time.} (65... Bxb4 $19) (65... Bd4 66.
c5+ Ka7 67. Qg2 g3 68. Be2 (68. Qc2 Qg1#) 68... Qh6+ 69. Qh3 Qxh3#) 0-1

