{[#]"It wasn't until Geller that we understood the King's Indian rightly".
This might have been one of the games inspiring Botvinnik to write these words.
} 15. a3 $6 {This practically wastes two tempi with respect to the previous
game, where Black had to provoke a2-a3 with ...Qb4-a5. Botvinnik probably did
not find useful moves that would not allow Black to create counterplay.} (15.
f4 {weakens the g1-a7 diagonal.} Be6 $5 16. b3 ({With the pawn on f2,} 16. Nxe6
Rxe6 17. Bxc5 {would win the pawn on a4 or else free the path for the e4-pawn,
but here Black takes with a check.} Qxc5+) 16... axb3 17. axb3 Qb4) (15. Kh2 h5
$5) (15. Bf4 $1 {is the strongest move. Geller gives} Ne6 (15... Bf8 16. Nf3
Rd8 {is somewhat better, but not really thrilling.}) ({Black's compensation is
questionable after} 15... Nfd7 16. Bxd6 Ne5 17. Bxe5) 16. Nxe6 (16. Bxd6 Nxd4
17. Rxd4 {looks even stronger.}) 16... Bxe6 17. Bxd6 Bxc4 18. e5 Nd7 {However,
due to the hanging pawn on a4 Black still has problems.} 19. Rd4 Qa6 20. f4 $16
) 15... Nfd7 (15... Be6 16. Nxe6 Rxe6 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 (17... dxc5 18. e5 $16) 18.
Nxa4 $14) (15... Bd7 16. Bf4 $16) 16. Bf1 Re7 $6 {At this height, not the best
plan. Black intends to double rooks (sometime in the future) in order to
attack e4. This implies returning with the knight to f6, thus wasting the
tempi he had got earlier.} (16... Nb6 $1 17. f4 Be6 {was more natural,
ensuring Black normal play.}) 17. f4 Nf6 18. Bf2 Bd7 19. e5 $6 {This only
plays into Black's hands. True, the knight will have to retreat to e8 but
later it can be transferred to c7-c6. It is strange that Geller considers this
pawn necessary in view of the threat ...Rae8.} (19. Nf3 $6 {[%csl Gd6]} Nfxe4
$1 (19... Ne8 20. g4 $36) (19... Rae8 20. Rxd6 Nfxe4 21. Nxe4 Bf5 22. Bxc5 Rxe4
23. Qf2 $18) 20. Nxe4 Bf5 21. Nfd2 (21. Bxc5 Rxe4 22. Rxe4 Qxc5+ 23. Kg2 d5 $17
) 21... Nxe4 22. Nxe4 d5 $15 {[%csl Gb2]}) (19. g4 $1 Rae8 20. Bg2 {was, of
course, necessary, even though Black's position would remain hard to break.} h5
(20... Bc8 $5) (20... Bxg4 21. hxg4 Nxg4 22. Bg3 $16) (20... h6 $5) 21. g5 Nh7
22. Qd2 Qc7 {followed by ...Qc8.}) 19... dxe5 20. fxe5 (20. Rxe5 Rxe5 21. fxe5
Ne8 22. Nf3 Bf5 23. Qe2 h5) 20... Ne8 21. Nf3 Bf5 22. Qe2 h5 23. Bd4 Nc7 24.
Qf2 (24. Nh4 $1 {was a better try to stay close to equality.} Bd7 25. Nf3 Rae8
26. Qf2 N7e6 27. Be3) 24... N7e6 25. Be3 Rae8 $17 {Black has reached a perfect
regrouping.} 26. Nh4 $6 Bxe5 (26... Ne4 27. Nxe4 Bxe4 28. Bd2 Qxe5 29. Bc3 {
Geller}) 27. Nxf5 gxf5 28. Qxf5 Ng7 29. Qf2 Bxc3 30. bxc3 Ne4 31. Qf4 Nxc3 32.
Rc1 Na2 33. Rcd1 Nc3 34. Rc1 Ne4 35. Re2 Qf5 36. g4 hxg4 37. hxg4 Qg6 38. Rg2
Ng5 39. Qxg5 Rxe3 40. Qxg6 fxg6 41. c5 Ne6 42. Rb2 Re7 43. Bc4 Kg7 44. Bxe6
R7xe6 45. g5 Rb3 46. Rxb3 axb3 47. Rd1 Re2 0-1

