{[#]In all these games, Black's play was a bit speculative and only White's
wrong planning led him to trouble. In all cases, White should have retained a
stable advantage. Therefore, Black started playing more flexibly, by delaying
the capture on d4. Here is a recent example of how play develops in the main
line.} 8... c6 9. h3 ({Another rule says that White should not remove his rook
from f1 before h2-h3.} 9. Re1 exd4 10. Nxd4 Ng4 11. h3 Qb6 {with counterplay.})
(9. Be3 {was an unsuccessful try by Botvinnik.} Ng4 10. Bg5 Qb6 11. h3 exd4 12.
Na4 Qa6 13. hxg4 b5 14. Nxd4 bxa4 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. e5 Qxc4 17. Bxa8 Nxe5 {
with overwhelming compensation for the exchange, Botvinnik, M-Smyslov, V
Moscow 1954 (0-1, 33).}) 9... Qb6 10. Re1 (10. d5 {is premature, yielding
Black free development.} Nc5 11. Re1 cxd5 12. cxd5 Bd7 $11) 10... exd4 {
Black should not delay this any more.} (10... Re8 {runs into} 11. d5 $1 {
when Re1 is more useful than ...Re8. In fact, the black rooks belongs to f8
for the purpose of a later ...f7-f5.} Nc5 12. Rb1 a5 13. Be3 Qc7 14. Nd2 Bd7
15. Bf1 $1 $14 {Using the square made available by the rook, White prevents ...
cxd5 followed by ...b7-b5.}) 11. Nxd4 Re8 {White experiences some problems
with developing his queenside.} 12. Re2 {The most consistent move.} (12. Nb3 {
releases the pressure in the centre.} Ne5 13. Be3 c5 14. Bf1 Be6 15. Nd5 Bxd5
16. exd5 Ne4 {Epishin,V (2635)-Kasparov,G (2805) Moscow 1995}) (12. b3 {
weakens the long diagonal, allowing} Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Qxd4 $11 {The rook on a1 is
hanging, ofering Black a tempo and} 14. Nf6+ $2 {does not work:} Nxf6 15. Qxd4
Rxe1+ 16. Bf1 (16. Kh2 Ng4+) 16... Ne8 17. Qd2 Rxf1+ 18. Kxf1 Bxa1 $19) 12...
Qb4 (12... Nxe4 $2 {does not work with the long diagonal unavailable:} 13. Nxe4
Qxd4 14. Nf6+ (14. Be3 Qxd1+ 15. Rxd1 {is also crushing.}) 14... Nxf6 15. Qxd4
Rxe2 16. Qd1 $18) 13. Rc2 {The only way to (indirectly) defend the pawn.} Nc5
14. Bd2 Qb6 15. Be3 Qc7 {Attacking e4.} 16. f3 a5 17. b3 Nfd7 18. Bf2 h5 {
We can notice that Black has reached the familiar setup after having induced
some lack of harmony in White's camp. It was precisely what Black should not
have got in the previous games: a few tempi to organise his counterplay.} 19.
Qf1 (19. f4 Nf6 20. Re2 h4 $5 21. g4 Nxg4 22. hxg4 Bxg4 23. Bxh4 a4 24. b4 Ne6
25. Nxe6 Rxe6 26. Rc1 Qb6+ 27. Kf1 Qxb4 28. Qd3 Bxc3 29. Qxc3 Bxe2+ 30. Kxe2
Qxc3 31. Rxc3 Rae8 {Stracey,N (2127) -Batchelor,P (2271) ICCF email 2016 
(½-½, 45)}) 19... Qb6 20. Rd1 (20. Rb1 {prevents the next move but fails to
defend d3.} Ne5 21. Kh1 Ned3 22. Bg1 Nb4 23. Rd2 a4 24. Nxa4 (24. a3 $2 axb3
25. axb4 Qxb4 $1 {is somewhat similar to Kotov-Geller.}) 24... Nxa4 25. bxa4
Qd8 26. a3 (26. Rxb4 c5 27. Rb5 cxd4 28. Bxd4 Bxd4 29. Rxd4 Rxa4 30. Qf2 Qf6
31. Rb2 b5 32. Rxb5 Rxa2 33. Qxa2 Qxd4 {with adequate compensation for the
pawn, due to White's weakened kingside position and passive bishop.}) 26... Na6
27. Nb3 Qe7 28. f4 f5 $11) 20... a4 $1 21. bxa4 (21. Rb1 Qb4 22. Nce2 axb3 23.
axb3 Nf8 $132 {[%cal Gf8e6] followed by ...N8e6.}) 21... Qa6 $2 (21... Qb4 $1
22. Rb1 Qa5 23. f4 Nb6 24. Nb3 Nxb3 25. Rxb3 Nd7 $5 {The control on c5 may be
more important than the a4-pawn.} 26. Kh2 Nc5 {with excellent play.}) (21...
Qa5 $5) 22. Nb3 Bf8 23. f4 Nxa4 24. Nb5 $1 $18 cxb5 25. cxb5 Qb6 26. Bxb6 Ndxb6
27. Rc7 Re7 28. Rxe7 Bxe7 29. Rc1 Nc5 30. e5 Nxb3 31. axb3 dxe5 32. Qf2 Nd7 33.
f5 Nf8 34. fxg6 Nxg6 35. Bd5 Nh8 36. Rc7 Kf8 37. Qc2 Bxh3 38. Qh7 1-0

