{[%evp 0,72,19,31,25,-11,52,35,32,2,5,14,31,33,33,46,42,14,53,28,0,-9,20,-17,
-18,-8,0,18,19,-11,66,5,38,34,41,24,45,61,73,21,-3,0,0,-48,0,-10,0,-15,29,-61,
-74,-65,-55,-110,-110,-224,-146,-191,-183,-183,-214,-192,-237,-237,-232,-232,
-233,-233,-240,-226,-155,-174,-161,-179,-153]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4.
g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 c6 9. b3 $5 {This is a modern
alternative to 9.h3. If Black plays in the same way, White has chances to
maintain his stability.} exd4 (9... Qb6 10. d5 cxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. cxd5 $14
{followed by Be3 and Nd2-c4 proves b2-b3 useful for gaining time.}) 10. Nxd4
Re8 11. h3 Nc5 12. Re1 Qb6 13. Be3 a5 14. Rb1 Bd7 15. Qc2 {This is just a
modern game featuring the same elements as the old ones. White's lack of
resoluteness will eventually put him in trouble.} Rad8 (15... Re7 $2 16. Na4
Nxa4 17. Nf5 $1) (15... Qc7 16. Rbd1 Re7 17. Bf4 $16) (15... h5 $5) 16. Rbd1
Qc7 17. f4 Re7 18. Bf2 Rde8 {Black is perfectly regrouped, but so is White.}
19. Re2 $6 {White hesitates for just one move, suddenly yielding Black
excellent play.} (19. g4 $1 Qc8 $6 20. f5 $1 {leaves black's pieces cramped.})
(19. Kh2 h5 {is given as unclear by Nunn, but Black misses one tempo to
generate adequate counterplay.} 20. a3 $1 Qc8 {preparing a later ...Bxg4
followed by ...Qxg4, the same as in the game.} 21. b4 axb4 22. axb4 Na6 23. Qb3
h4 24. gxh4 $1 Nh5 25. Nde2 {With the black knight passive on a6, White is
able to maintain the control.}) 19... Qc8 {Black has a dangerous initiative
already. The lines below belong to John Nunn.} (19... h5 $5) 20. Kh2 (20. g4 $2
Bxg4 21. hxg4 Qxg4 $17) 20... h5 $1 $15 {[/\ h4]} 21. Bg1 (21. Rde1 h4 22. g4
Bxg4 23. hxg4 Nxg4+ 24. Kh1 Nxf2+ 25. Rxf2 Bxd4 $19) (21. Ree1 h4 22. g4 Bxg4
23. hxg4 Qxg4 {(><f4)} 24. Qc1 Bh6 25. Nde2 Ncxe4 $17) 21... h4 22. gxh4 (22.
g4 Bxg4 23. hxg4 Qxg4 24. Rf1 Nh5 $17) 22... Nh5 23. Rf1 Bf6 $15 {[/\ Bh4 ><g3]
} (23... Bh6 $1 $17 {Marin}) 24. Rf3 Bxh4 25. a3 Bf6 {[/\ Nf4]} 26. Bf2 $2 (26.
b4 axb4 27. axb4 Na6 $17) (26. Kh1 $1 Bg7 {/\ Bh6=/+}) 26... Nxf4 $1 $19 {^D}
27. Nxc6 (27. Rxf4 Be5 {(/\ g5)} 28. Bg3 Bxd4) 27... Bxc6 28. Rxf4 Be5 29. Bg3
Ne6 $1 (29... Bxf4 30. Bxf4 $17) 30. Rh4 Bxg3+ (30... Nd4 $2 31. Bxe5 $1 {
/\ Qd2-h6}) 31. Kxg3 Nd4 32. Qd2 Nxe2+ 33. Nxe2 Qe6 {(1.40/1.26)} 34. Qxa5 Qe5+
