{[#]} 9. b3 {In 2003 I analysed the idea played in this game together with the
Romanian women team, as their trainer and captain. I had the occasion to use
it only 13 years later, but everything seems allright.} (9. h3 {I should
mention that the same idea does not work here:} a6 10. Be3 b5 11. dxe5 (11. c5
$16 {is also strong}) 11... dxe5 {transposing to Kortschnoj-Penrose.}) 9... a6
$1 {Since White has spent a tempo on the weakening move b2-b3, Black is
entitled to change plans.} 10. dxe5 (10. h3 b5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Qc2 Qe7 {
is comfortable for Black. White not only is a tempo down with respect to
Kortschnoj's game but does not have the b3-square for his knights, either.}) (
10. Ba3 Qa5 11. Bb2 Re8 {leads to a position White should avoid since the
bishop is not well placed on b2.}) (10. a4 a5 $11) 10... dxe5 11. Ba3 Re8 12.
Bd6 (12. c5 $2 Bf8 $17 {Nguyen,N (2629) -Adhiban,B (2677) Tbilisi 2017 (0-1,
30)}) 12... Bf8 13. Re1 Bxd6 (13... Kg7 $5) 14. Qxd6 Qe7 15. Rad1 Kg7 16. Bh3
Qxd6 17. Rxd6 {White has managed to exchange queens, but this does not ensure
him an advantage. The difference is that Black, too, has exchanged the
dark-squared bishops, ensuring him against any strategic problems. Besides,
his king could go to e7, now.} Nf8 (17... Nc5 $1 {was more active.} 18. Bxc8
Raxc8 19. b4 (19. Kg2 a5 {is very pleasant for Black.}) 19... Ncd7 20. Red1 (
20. c5 a5 21. a3 axb4 22. axb4 Ra8 23. Red1 Nf8 $15) 20... Nb6 21. Nd2 (21. c5
Nc4 22. R6d3 Nb2 $17) 21... Rcd8 $15) 18. Bxc8 Raxc8 19. Kf1 N6d7 (19... N8d7
20. Red1 Rc7 21. Ke2 Nc5 22. Ke3 b5 23. b4 Nb7 24. R6d2 bxc4 $11) 20. Red1 Rc7
21. Ke2 Re7 (21... b5 $1) 22. Ke3 a5 23. Ne1 Ne6 24. R6d2 Nec5 (24... f5 $5)
25. Nd3 h5 26. Nxc5 Nxc5 27. Rd8 $14 Red7 28. Ra8 Rxd1 29. Nxd1 b6 30. Rb8 Nd7
31. Ra8 Nc5 32. Rb8 Nd7 1/2-1/2

