dxc5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. e5 Nfd7 11. f4 Nc6 $13) 8... b5 9. cxb5 axb5 (9... h5 10.
O-O h4 11. Nh1 axb5 12. Bxb5 Qb6 $44 {1-0 (60) Roshka,Y (2476) -Nenezic,M 
(2528) Tornelo INT 2020}) 10. Bxb5 Ba6 11. O-O Bxb5 12. Nxb5 Na6 $44 {[%cal
Ga6c7]}) 5... O-O 6. Be2 ({Nowadays very fashionable} 6. h3 e5 7. d5 ({Harmless
} 7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8) 7... a5 (7... Nh5 8. g3 f5 (8... a5 9. Be2 Na6 10.
Nh2 Nf6 11. Ng4 $13) 9. exf5 gxf5 10. Nh4 (10. Ng5 Qe8 $1 {0-1 (27) Raznikov,D
(2488)-Rodshtein,M (2639)/Acre 2013/Mega2013 Update 16 (27)}) 10... Nf6 (10...
Nf4 11. Bd2 $14) 11. Bg5 Na6 {big theory}) 8. g4 Na6 9. Be3 Nc5 10. Nd2 c6 11.
Be2 a4 12. g5 {very complex play} (12. Bxc5 dxc5 13. Nxa4 Bh6 $44 (13... b5 $5)
) 12... Nfd7 (12... Ne8) 13. h4 f5 (13... Qa5)) 6... e5 7. O-O Nc6 (7... Bg4 8.
dxe5 Bxf3 9. exf6 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Bxf6 11. Bh6 $14 {1-0 (30) Firouzja,A (2728)
-Paravyan, D (2653) Lichess.org INT 2020}) (7... h6 {played by Giri recently}
8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Be3 (9. Nxe5 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxh6 Bxb2 $11
) 9... Nbd7 10. Qc1 Kh7 11. Rd1 $36 {0-1 (42) Lysyj,I (2605)-Giri,A (2764)
Chess.com INT 2020}) (7... Na6) (7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Re8 9. f3 c6 10. Kh1 $14) 8.
d5 Ne7 9. b4 a5 {White has a choice between 10. ba5 and 10. Ba3} (9... Nh5 10.
Re1 f5 11. a4 $5 {last word for White} (11. Ng5 Nf6 12. Bf3 c6 {old main line})
11... Nf6 12. a5 h6 13. Ra3 (13. exf5 $5 Bxf5 (13... gxf5 14. Nh4) (13... Nxf5
$5) 14. Ra2 g5 15. h3 Qe8 16. Nh2 a6 17. Ng4 $14 {1-0 (41) Ding,L (2791)
-Nakamura,H (2736) chess24.com INT 2020}) 13... f4 14. h4 Rf7 15. c5 {
promising for White Giri,A (2764)-Korobov, A (2688) chess24.com INT 2020}) 10.
Ba3 (10. bxa5 Rxa5 11. a4 c5 {games}) 10... axb4 11. Bxb4 b6 12. a4 Re8 {
Black is going to prepare c7-c5, that will seriously complicate White
attacking ideas on the queenside. There are two key games I recommned to check}
({Natural} 12... Ne8 {looks fine} 13. Nd2 f5 14. Nb3 Nf6 {games}) 13. Re1 {and}
(13. Nd2 {now there is no need in Bf8 and Black can play} c5 {at once} 14. Ba3
Rf8 15. Bb2 Ne8 16. Nb5 Bh6 17. Ra3 f5 {Black was fine in Ernst-Van Campen 2013
}) (13. Qd3 Nf5 $1) 13... Bf8 14. Bf1 c5 15. Ba3 Bg7 16. Bb2 Rf8 17. Nb5 Ne8
18. Nd2 f5 19. Bc3 {this occurred in Fressinet, L (2700)-Grischuk,A (2764)/
Beijing 2012 now thematic} Bh6 {would help Black to develop his counterplay on
the kingside.} *

