{[%evp 0,85,80,63,56,-31,66,37,32,35,24,50,34,36,32,31,57,65,75,56,64,34,30,34,
27,23,19,19,69,64,62,84,84,76,88,61,68,50,47,54,128,163,163,152,156,132,73,-9,
39,39,34,41,32,32,47,5,-1,15,0,0,32,17,17,0,16,-135,-172,-343,-72,-163,-389,
-479,-484,-467,-518,-518,-514,-598,-632,-918,-647,-1441,-875,-1045,-1276,-1976,
-1107,-1136] Dear readers of "Modern chess", In this article, I will examine
the tactical and strategical ideas for both colors in the most popular system
in King's Indian Defense - Mar del Plata. This system becomes popular around
60 years ago at the early 50s, mainly because of the efforts of Mark Taimanov
for White and the Serbian (Yugoslavian) legendary player Svetlozar Gligoric
for Black. The popularity increased after the following game which becomes a
model game showing how to play the KID with Black and many generations of
strong players are learning from it. There are hundreds of games, books and
videos which give some long forced lines here, but my idea is not to provide
you with an opening repertoire, but to teach you how to handle the arising
positions. In these positions, computer evaluations are irrelevant, since the
computer always gives a big advantage for White even after first ten moves,
mainly because of the space advantage. This is not an objective evaluation and
a number of players have lost their games because of their trust to the
engines. What really matters here is the understanding. Usually, the outcome
is favorable for the side one who manages to execute his plan first. I can
recommend you sincerely to learn how to play this line for both sides because
this is one of those fundamental structures in chess which is must know.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 {This is to so-called
Classical system which is the most popular weapon against KID.} e5 7. O-O Nc6
8. d5 Ne7 {I should stop here and explain you the plans for both sides. White
has space advantage and his main plan is to open a file on the queenside and
invade opponent's camp. Black's plan is to organize an attack on the kingside
by means f7-f5-f4 followed by the advance of "g" and "h". Later on, he could
regroup his pieces and attack White's king by opening the g-file or by pushing
g4-g3. Black has no much space and should play precisely, in order not to find
himself doomed to passivity. He should know exactly how to arrange his pieces
in the best way. White should choose now how to arrange his pieces: to stay
with the Knight on f3 - square (systems with 9.b4 or 9.Qc2) and to met
eventual f7-f5 by means Ng5 or to play Ne1-d3, Nd2-c4 maneuvers with an idea
to met f7-f5 by playing f2-f3. In the first part of this article, we will see
a classical approach of handling this position: White plays Ne1 followed by
Be3 and f3. This set-up seems very natural. White puts all his pawns on the
light squares and use his dark-squared bishop to cover the dark squares. In
this setup, the game becomes pretty sharp because Black's hope is to organize
a successful attack against White's king and sometimes sacrifices a lot of
material, giving White a free hand on the queenside.} 9. Ne1 Nd7 {There is a
discussion where to put the knight - on e8 or on d7. The game move was always
much more popular and flexible because being on d7, the knight covers c5
square and gives Black the chance to play Rf6 - h6 followed by Qe8 - h5.} 10.
Be3 {The move 10.Nd3 is also possible, but this is a matter of discussion of
the next games.} f5 11. f3 f4 {Remember that this move is good only after
f2-f3 If the pawn is on f2, white can answer it with Bg4, followed by an
exchange of the light-squared bishops. Without them, Black's attack is not so
dangerous anymore and White's position becomes almost strategically winning.
This position was always a matter of discussion for players at all levels from
World Champions to club players. My opinion is that it is too risky to play
like this with White - even If your strategical ideas are realized, one small
mistake can lead to a disaster. On the other hand, Black's play is much more
easier and straightforward. It is always more pleasant to attack opponent's
King than his queenside.} 12. Bf2 {The bishop seems to be perfectly placed
here. The drawback is that Black won a tempo with his previous move and now is
ready to start an attack.} g5 {I should mention that instead of this move,
Gary Kasparov advocates 13...h5. The idea is to prevent the opponent from
closing the kingside by 14.g2-g4. Still, most of the King's Indian specialists
prefer the move in the text, because it is more flexible and allow the plan
Rf6-h6 which we will see in the game Korchnoi - Cheparinov.} 13. Nd3 {After
years of investigation, the theory comes to conclusion that this move is not
very accurate.} (13. a4 $5 {this move is Victor Korchnoi's patent and he has a
lot of spectacular wins with it. The idea is to win space on a queenside and
to give white an option to develop the rook via a3, from where it can defend
the King side}) (13. Rc1 {followed by pawn sacrifice 14.c5 is invented by
Croatian GM Zdenko Kozul and became a main line nowadays.}) 13... Nf6 {Black
is preparing g5-g4!} (13... Rf6 {This is another setup for Black which we
should discuss in the later games.}) 14. c5 Ng6 15. Rc1 Rf7 {This is the way
how you should regroup your pieces! Every KID - player should know this plan.
Rook is coming on g7 to support the g5-g4 - break and to cover the very
important c7 - square. The bishop is coming to f8 to protect the d6 - pawn.}
16. Rc2 {Logical, but slow move which gives Black a chance to continue with
the attack.} Bf8 17. cxd6 cxd6 18. Qd2 {Another slow move the idea of which is
to prepare doubling the rooks on the c - file. Now the queen no longer covers
the g4-square and Black is the first to start concrete actions.} g4 $1 {
Blafck should play g4 in the first possible moment.} 19. Rfc1 {White's pieces
look "ideally placed". If Black takes on f3 then the white king will have the
nice h1-square. Later on, the possible invasion on the queenside could decide
the game. Black had something else in mind.} g3 $1 {Very nice positional
sacrifice. Now Black opens files and diagonals for his pieces. White's king
will be much weaker and the Black's Knight has the wonderful f4-square. Also,
the diagonal h6-c1 would be a very nice place for dark squared bishop. This
pawn sacrifice is the key motif and the most common attacking idea for Black.}
20. hxg3 fxg3 21. Bxg3 {this should be played.} ({If} 21. Be3 Nh5 {followed by
Qh4 decides the game quickly in Black's favour}) 21... Nh5 22. Bh2 Be7 {
The bishop is coming either on g5 or on h4} 23. Nb1 {With an idea to met 23...
Bg5 by 24.Rxc8.} (23. Nd1 {One of the main advantages of the KID defense is
that engines always evaluate the position in White's favour. For example,
after this move, the computer gives almost +1. I should disagree with this
evaluation. One advice: Always continue analyzing a little bit deeper. Here
for example after 23...Bd7 followed by Bg5 the engines start liking Black's
position more and more after each move.}) 23... Bd7 24. Qe1 Bg5 {One more
pieces is joining the attack.} 25. Nd2 Be3+ 26. Kh1 Qg5 {Her majesty is also
coming.} 27. Bf1 Raf8 {The last Black's pieces comes into play.} 28. Rd1 {
According to Bronstein, this move is the last mistake in the game and White's
position is lost after it.} (28. Nc4 $1 {Is the best move here, but not
changing much the evaluation of the position.} Bxc1 29. Rxc1 Rf6 {With an
exchange up and attack.}) 28... b5 $1 {Covers the c4-square.} 29. a4 a6 30.
axb5 axb5 31. Rc7 {White finally invades the queenside, but there is nothing
there.} Rg7 {Black is preparing Nh4 with multiple threats.} 32. Nb3 Nh4 33. Rc2
Bh3 (33... Rxf3 $1 {this ends the game immediately} 34. gxf3 $2 Qg1+ 35. Bxg1
Rxg1+ 36. Kh2 Nxf3# {Nice finish.}) 34. Qe2 {When you attack with 7 pieces,
always the combination should exist.} Nxg2 35. Bxg2 Bxg2+ 36. Qxg2 Qh4 {
With the deadly threat of Ng3!} 37. Qxg7+ Kxg7 38. Rg2+ Kh8 39. Ne1 {White
sacrifices his queen, but still can't stop the mate coming.} Nf4 40. Rg3 Bf2
41. Rg4 Qh3 42. Nd2 h5 43. Rg5 {After 43...Rg8 White has no defense from the
mate. This win impressed a lot the chess world at that time. One of the best
KID players for White was smashed without making any visible mistake. I
suggest to every KID player to remember every single move of this game,
because it is the main reason that this opening is so popular today.} 0-1

