{This is a model game for Black. He played in an extremely aggressive style
without losing any single tempo.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5.
e4 d6 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 f4 12. Bf2 g5
13. b4 {This move has a dubious reputation now, but back in the time, it was
tried by some very strong players including J.Picket. The idea is obvious -
White is preparing c4-c5.} Nf6 14. c5 {The idea c4-c5 is played, but somehow,
the move b2-b4 looks like a loss of a tempo. As we already know, the time is
the most significant factor in this structure.} Ng6 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. Rc1 {
White is playing the most natural moves. His idea is to go for Nb5, after
taking the control over the c-file.} Rf7 $1 {This is the right plan. Again, I
insist on the fact that any moves on the queenside like 16...a6 just provoke
weaknesses and lose time for the attack. Also, h5 is possible, but Kasparov
wants to leave this square free for his f6-knight.} 17. a4 (17. Nb5 g4) 17...
Bf8 18. a5 Bd7 19. Nb5 {White makes use of the fact that the c7-square is
available now, but leaves e4 pawn without protection.} g4 $1 20. Nc7 {The game
becomes very concrete. White is ready to meet 20...Rc8 by means of Ne6 when
Black would be in trouble. That's why it is time for our typical attacking
move.} g3 $1 21. Nxa8 ({Of course, critical was:} 21. hxg3 fxg3 22. Bxg3 Nh5 {
there is no way back, the rook on a8 is not important at all.} 23. Bh2 Bh6 {
again Black simply activates his pieces} 24. Rc3 Bf4 25. Bxf4 Ngxf4 26. Nxa8
Qh4 {This is the final blow - Black is a rook down, but his attack is
unstoppable,}) 21... Nh5 {clearing the path for the queen.} 22. Kh1 gxf2 23.
Rxf2 Ng3+ {very strong move again. White can't take the knight.} 24. Kg1 Qxa8
25. Bc4 a6 $1 {With the idea to activate the queen via a7. Black's position is
already winning, but it is interesting to observe how much energy has in every
Kasparov's move.} 26. Qd3 Qa7 27. b5 axb5 28. Bxb5 Nh1 {Nice finish. Black
wins a piece so White resigns. Fabulous game for Black and extremely
instructive. This is the way how Black should handle the position - energetic
play without losing any time and without hesitation to sacrifice material.} 0-1

