{In this game, we will see the interesting idea of keeping the bishop on g7
and play 16...h5 instead. This gives Black a chance for another regrouping
starting with 21...Qf8.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6.
Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. f3 f5 11. Be3 f4 12. Bf2 {Again, we
have reached our main position. This time, I want to show you one recent game
between two American superstars. Wesley So just couple of days ago won
Sinquefield 2016, but from last year he had not very good memories from this
tournament. One of his losses was this one.} g5 13. Nd3 {As we mention before,
this is the best square for the Knight. From this position, the knight not
only supports the c4-c5 advance, but at the same time could participate either
in the defence (by playing Nf2) or in the attack (by means of Nb4).} Ng6 14. c5
Nf6 15. Rc1 Rf7 {Starting the famous Naidorf's manoeuvre.} 16. Kh1 h5 (16...
Bf8 {is the most common move in this position, but Black has something else in
mind.}) 17. cxd6 cxd6 18. Nb5 {Engines like this move a lot, but I can't see
the point. It looks like this is just a waste of time which is proven later in
the game.} a6 19. Na3 b5 {Black stops the idea Nc4-b6 followed by the exchange
of Black's light-squared bishop. Now c6-square is available, but the problem
for White is that only one knight can go there.} 20. Rc6 {Both players blitzed
the moves until now, but it seems to me that Black evaluates the position much
better. Black is ready for an active play on the kingside, while White can't
do anything on the queenside.} g4 21. Qc2 Qf8 {Here we can see the idea of 16..
.h5 instead of 16...Bf8.} 22. Rc1 Bd7 23. Rc7 (23. Nb4 {makes more sense here,
but Black's position is still easy to play.} g3) 23... Bh6 24. Be1 h4 {the
threat is h3} 25. fxg4 {After this move Black plays very energetically,
sacrificing a lot of material.} f3 $1 {Opens new files and diagonals for his
pieces.} ({The move} 25... Bxg4 $6 {just leads to the exchange of some pieces.}
26. Rxf7 Qxf7 27. Bxg4 Nxg4 28. Qc7 {White is at least OK here.}) 26. gxf3 Nxe4
$1 {Another spectacular move.} 27. Rd1 $2 {this loses on the spot, but it is
hard to come up with something better for White.} (27. Rxd7 {ruins to} Rxf3 $1
28. Bxf3 Qxf3+ 29. Qg2 Qxd3 {With a winning position for Black.}) 27... Rxf3
28. Rxd7 Rf1+ 29. Kg2 Be3 $1 {Nice move which introduces the deadly threat of
Rg1} 30. Bg3 hxg3 31. Rxf1 Nh4+ {White's positon colapsed.} 32. Kh3 Qh6 33. g5
{So can resign even here because there is a forced mate.} Nxg5+ 34. Kg4 Nhf3 {
Nice move, now Qh3 is the threat.} 35. Nf2 Qh4+ 36. Kf5 Rf8+ 37. Kg6 Rf6+ $1 {
One final sacrifice.} 38. Kxf6 Ne4+ 39. Kg6 Qg5# {Spectacular win for Black,
which shows us how careful we should be when we analyze this position with
engines. My computer likes a lot White's position after move 20, but it failed
to offer improvement for White after that.} 0-1

