{In this game, we will see the plan with Rf6 - h6, Qe8-h5} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6
3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Nf3 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10.
Be3 f5 11. f3 f4 12. Bf2 g5 {The first 12 moves are the same like in the
previous game. In this game, the legendary Victor Kortschnoj decides to avoid
his favorite 13.a4 and to play the modern line 13.Rc1. His opponent is the
Bulgarian strong GM Ivan Cheparinov who manages to crush his much more
experienced opponent in a style.} 13. Rc1 {The idea that we mention before.
Black doesn't hide his intention to go for a direct attack. The idea is pretty
simple. Rf8-f6-h6 with Qe8-h5 and it is not easy for White to defend the
h2-pawn} Rf6 ({An important nuance is that} 13... Nf6 $6 {is not very accurate
here, because allows c4-c5!} 14. c5 $1 {White's attack seems to be faster.}) ({
Black should start with} 13... Ng6 $5) 14. c5 {White is sacrificing material,
in order to win some tempos and open the c-file.} Nxc5 15. b4 Na6 {This is
necessary.} ({Unfortunately} 15... Nd7 $2 {ruins to} 16. Nb5 $16 {which is the
point of White's idea.}) 16. Nb5 Rh6 {Black doesn't care about his queenside
and completely abandons it.} ({the idea to protect the a7-pawn with} 16... b6 {
is a typical mistake. Now, in many variations, the Na6 is hanging.}) 17. Nxa7
Bd7 {The light-squared bishop is Black's most important attacking piece and we
should avoid exchanging it. The rule says that If White manages to exchange it,
then the attack on the kingside will be less effective and in the most of the
cases, White is better.} 18. Bxa6 {White exchanges the defender of the c7 pawn,
but now he has problems to cover the extremely important g4-square.} bxa6 19.
Qc2 {It is impossible to protect c7} g4 $1 {Black leaves the queenside, but
organizes a strong attack on the other part of the board.} (19... Qe8 {is also
possible} 20. Qxc7 {This is very instructive moment. Black should play 20...
g4! not Qh5 immediately.} Qh5 $2 {Looks tempting, but White has a wonderful
defense.} 21. h4 $3 $18 {1-0 (30) Zhao,X (2506)-Ju,W (2558) Huaian 2016}) 20.
Qxc7 Qe8 21. g3 {White wants to bring his major pieces into the defence via
the second rank. Nevertheless, this move weakens the king even more.} (21. fxg4
$1 {was better} Bxg4 22. Bb6 {with the idea to meet} Qh5 23. Nf3 Bxf3 24. Rxf3
Qxh2+ 25. Kf1 {And White manages to survive, 25...Qh1 will be well met by Bg1.}
) 21... Kh8 {Nice idea! Black wants to execute another typical manoeuvre - Ne7
- g8 - f6} 22. Rc2 Ng8 23. fxg4 {The drawback of this move is that e4 pawn is
desperately weak.} Bxg4 24. Bb6 Qg6 {Black increase the pressure - g3 and e4 -
pawns are very weak.} 25. Nc6 {It is not difficult to spot that White's pieces
on the queenside are complitely useless.} fxg3 26. Nd8 {Trying to make some
threats, but Black has a simple solution.} Rxd8 27. Qxd8 gxh2+ {And White
resigns due to the following variation.} 28. Rxh2 Bf3+ 29. Rg2 Bxg2 30. Nxg2
Qxe4 {with an easily winning position. It was interesting to see how so
experienced player as Viktor Korthcnoi was outplayed so easily.} 0-1

