{In this game we will see the other very interesting plan for Black: Kh8 - Ng8
- Bh6} 1. d4 g6 2. c4 Bg7 3. e4 d6 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6
8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 Ne8 10. Be3 f5 11. f3 {I would like to show you one more plan
for Black. Even If it is not so popular, it is always useful to have it in
your arsenal of weapons.} Kh8 {Begining of the plan with the idea to play Ng8,
followed by Bh6 and later close the position.} 12. c5 {White is in a hurry to
open the queenside which is the right plan in this position.} Ng8 13. cxd6 (13.
a4 $1 Bh6 14. Bxh6 Nxh6 15. Nd3 f4 16. a5 a6 17. b4 g5 18. cxd6 $16 {White
manages to open the queenside before Black's attack becomes serious. 1-0 (59)
Swayams,M (2444)-Hillarp Persson,T (2546) Douglas 2015}) 13... cxd6 14. Qd2 $5
{White is stopping the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, but the queen is
not staying very good at d2-square.} f4 {Black closed the kingside and switch
to the classical plan with pushing g and h pawns.} 15. Bf2 h5 ({If} 15... g5 {
then} 16. g4 {deserves consideration}) 16. Nb5 a6 17. Nc3 {Strange maneuver.
If White wants to provoke a7-a6, then it makes sense to play 17.Na3 with the
idea to provoke further weaknesses such as b7-b5.} Bd7 18. Qd1 {One more tempo
should be lost here. It is funny that the engines give almost +1 for White
here. In my opinion, the game is pretty complex and Black has his chances.} Rb8
{Obviously with the idea to met 19.Na4 by means of b5} 19. Na4 $2 {Why White
wants to lose so many tempos?!} (19. a4 $5 {make sense here.}) 19... b5 20. Nc3
g5 21. b4 Nh6 22. a4 bxa4 23. Nxa4 Rxb4 {Black accepts the challenge. Now the
queenside is missing and the game will be decided on the other side of the
board.} 24. Nd3 Rb8 25. Qd2 a5 ({White doesn't want to allow Nb4, but the
immediate g4 is also strong.} 25... g4 {with the same ideas like in the game})
26. Nab2 g4 $5 {Finally the attack begins, Black's plan is simple: to activate
his pieces and open the kingside by taking on f3 or playing g4-g3} 27. Rxa5 {
White equalizes the material, but can't make any threats in the center or on
the queenside. At this point, Black regroups his pieces for a dangerous attack.
} Rg8 {the rook is much more useful on the g-file} 28. Nc4 Nf7 {The Knight is
protecting d6 and can come to g5.} 29. Nb4 {We can see how hopeless is White's
position. He can't make any single threat} g3 30. Ba7 ({After:} 30. hxg3 {
Black could follow with} fxg3 31. Bxg3 Bh6 32. Qe1 Rxb4 {And White's position
colapsed}) 30... Qh4 31. hxg3 fxg3 32. Rb1 {White's hopes are based on this
resource. Now the king can come to safety on f1 and the bishop will return to
g1.} Bh6 {Black is the first to improve all his pieces.} 33. Qc2 Qh2+ 34. Kf1
Qh1+ 35. Bg1 h4 {The most straightforward move. White's position will colaplse
quickly after h4-h3} 36. f4 h3 {White resigns} 0-1

