{In this game, we will see one of the most beautiful combinations in this
structure.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O
Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Nd2 {In this game we will discuss a different system - 9. Nd2.
This system is connected with 10.b4. The idea is that after the advance c4-c5,
the knight will have the wonderful c4-square. Black has a number of choices:}
Ne8 {This move is Nakamura's favorite. The game is very sharp. As in previous
games . Black almost abandonned the queenside and push all his efforts on the
Kingside.} (9... a5 {The most popular is 9...a7-a5 which leads to a more
positional game. Black is trying to slow down White's play on the queenside
and little by little to prepare his counterplay with f7-f5.} 10. Rb1 Bd7 11. b3
c6 12. Bb2 Bh6 13. a3 c5 14. Bc1 Ne8 15. b4 {1/2 (28) Beliavsky,A (2623)
-Bacrot,E (2711) Jerusalem 2015}) (9... Nd7 10. b4) (9... c5 10. dxc6 (10. Rb1
Ne8 11. b4 b6 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Nb3 f5 14. Bg5 {1/2 (31) Gurevich,M (2688)
-Hebden,M (2560) Clichy 2001}) 10... bxc6 11. b4 d5 12. Ba3 Re8 13. b5 d4 {
1-0 (45) Harikrishna, P (2725)-Socko,B (2614) Doha 2014}) 10. b4 f5 11. c5 Nf6
(11... f4 $2 {As we already know, this move is a huge positional blunder. It
allows an exchange of the light-squared bishops with an almost winning
position for White.} 12. Bg4 g5 13. Ba3 Nf6 14. Bxc8 Rxc8 15. f3 h5 16. Nc4 Qd7
17. b5 g4 18. Rc1 gxf3 19. Qxf3 {1-0 (32) Marin,M (2583)-Fernandez Rubio,R 
(2019) Benasque 2009}) 12. f3 f4 13. Nc4 g5 14. a4 Ng6 15. Ba3 Rf7 {Again, we
have this well known maneuvre. Black is ready to defend d6-pawn by means of
Bf8.} 16. b5 dxc5 (16... Bf8 {This is another continuation which also deserved
consideration.}) 17. Bxc5 h5 18. a5 {White is planning to play b5-b6 followed
by Nb5.} g4 19. b6 g3 {There is no time for defence. Black should hurry with
the attack.} 20. Kh1 {Clever move played with the idea to met an eventual Qh4
with Bg1} Nh7 21. Nb5 (21. bxc7 $2 {is well met by} Rxc7 {And Black wins an
important tempo} 22. Bg1 h4 {with an idea h4-h3} 23. h3 Bxh3 $1 24. gxh3 Qc8 $1
{With a winning position.}) 21... Qh4 22. Bg1 Bh3 (22... Ng5 $5 {was probably
better with the idea Nh3!} 23. Nxc7 Nh3) 23. Re1 $4 {This move is a horrible
mistake, but you should agree that the following combination is very beautiful
and it is easy to be missed over the board.} (23. gxh3 $1 Qxh3 {This looks
very dangerous, but White has a very powerfull defensive resource.} (23... g2+
$2 {is just bad here} 24. Kxg2 Ng5 25. Kh1 {And the King is absolutely safe on
h1}) 24. Rf2 $1 {The only move, but it is enough for an advantage.} gxf2 25.
Bxf2 {Black has no attack and White's pieces are much better placed.}) 23...
Bxg2+ $1 {Black gives a forced mate in 6 moves.} 24. Kxg2 Qh3+ {The point of
the combination, after the bishop Black is sacrifice the queen for nothing.}
25. Kxh3 Ng5+ {this knight which seemed very passive on the h7-square gives
mate at the end.} 26. Kg2 Nh4+ 27. Kf1 g2+ 28. Kf2 Nh3# {Absolutely brilliant
finish. This game shows us that even in the positions, where White is clearly
better, every single mistake could be fatal.} 0-1

