{Dear chess friends, In this article, we continue to deal with the typical
King's Indian structures. As in the first article on this subject, I am going
to show all the typical postional and tactical motifs in the structure. On the
diagram, you could see the structure that will be examined in the article. It
arises when White meets the move f7-f5 by means of exf5. The exchange exf5 is
good when Black can't respond with Nxf5. If Black takes on f5 with the bishop,
then after g2-g4, White obtains a full control over the e4-square. If gxf5,
the most popular response then is f2-f4 fixing the pawn on f5 and provoking
e5-e4. In this position, the rule is that if Black has a pawn on c5, he has an
acceptable position because he controls the important d4 - square; if Black's
pawn is on c7, then White is better, because could use the d4-square. In the
game, Flor - Petrosian we will see one of the rare examples when Bxf5 is a
good move. This is usually when the dark-squared bishops are missing. In
Botvinnik - Boleslavsky, the Patriarch of the Soviet chess school shows us how
to handle this position with White. In Petrosian - Stein and Bronstein -
Petrosian, we can see Black's defensive ideas. In Kuzmin - Taimanov, we can
see why exf5 does not give any advantage when Black has a Knight on e7 and can
answer it with Nxf5. The last example is a recent game of mine against the
silver medalist from the European Championship 2016. I managed to outplay my
high rated opponent and eventually lost a completely winning position in a
time trouble.}  *

[Event "Moscow"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "1950.11.24"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Flohr, Salo"]
[Black "Petrosian, Tigran V"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "E94"]
[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/1pp4p/3p2p1/p1nPpp2/2P1P3/2N5/PPQ1BPPP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 16"]
[PlyCount "13"]
[EventDate "1950.??.??"]
[EventRounds "17"]
[EventCountry "URS"]

{This is our starting position. How we can evaluate it? White has a space
advantage as usual in KID. On the other hand, Black managed to exchange the
dark-squared bishops which definitely will be in his favor if White decides to
transpose to the Mar Del Plata - pawn structure after 16.f3 f4!.} 16. exf5 {
White decides to open the game and leaves black with three choices : 16...
Rxf5?!, 16...gxf5?! and the move played in the game Bxf5!} Bxf5 $1 {I will try
to explain why this move is the correct one here. You should remember one
simple rule: without dark-squared bishops is preferable to take on f5 with a
bishop instead of taking with a pawn. Taking with the pawn seriously weakens
the kingside and after some rook lift on the third rank, in the future,
Black's king will be in danger. An important nuance is that without
dark-squared bishops Black shouldn't be scared to put his pawns on the dark
squares (g6 - g5) and to try to fight against f2-f4. Also, by taking with the
bishop, Black wins a tempo and can use the e4 square for exchanging the
knights.} (16... Rxf5 {This move shouldn't be considered at all. Even if in
this particular position, it is not so bad. The reason is simple - Black is
not fighting for the light squares or for the important e4 - square.} 17. Bg4
$1 Rf4 18. Bxc8 Qxc8 19. b3 {White has an obvious plan - f3, a3, b4, Ne4 with
an advantage.}) (16... gxf5 {The most obvious and typical move. Here, however,
this is a mistake since Black allows 17.f4 with a pleasant position for White.}
17. f4 e4 {Even if Black postpones this move for a while, sooner or later, it
would be provoked. Afterwards, White will have at least two very promising
ideas. One is to play 18.Nb5 - d4, bring the queen to c3 and the rook to e3.
In such position, Black's King will be in danger. Another idea is the
classical approach to bring the queen to d4 followed by transferring the
Knight to e3 with a good play on the both flangs.}) 17. Qc1 g5 {Petrosian is
consistent with his plan.} 18. Qe3 Qf6 19. Rd2 Bd7 20. Ne4 Nxe4 21. Qxe4 Qf4
22. Qe3 {At this point, the draw was agreed. I think that Petrosian's decision
is premature, because Black can enjoy a risk-free position . Some ideas to
improve the position can be 22...Kg7, Rf7, Raf8 and so on. Anyway, this is a
very instructive example by the 9th World Champion on a theme "when to take on
f5 with a bishop".} 1/2-1/2

[Event "URS-ch12"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "1940.09.06"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Botvinnik, Mikhail"]
[Black "Boleslavsky, Isaak"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "E68"]
[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bqnrk1/2p3bp/1p1p2p1/p1nPpp2/2P1P3/2NNB1PP/PP1Q1PB1/R4RK1 w - - 0 15"]
[PlyCount "69"]
[EventDate "1940.09.05"]
[EventRounds "19"]
[EventCountry "URS"]

{Now, let's take a look at a model game of how to play this pawn structure
with White. The diagram position can arise from all the variations of KID.} 15.
exf5 $1 {The rule that you should remember is that this move is good when
Black can't take on f5 with the Knight! Now, Black has 3 choices:} gxf5 (15...
Rxf5 $2 {This move is just bad.} 16. g4 $1 Rf7 17. f4 $1 {White is more
prepared for opening the position.}) (15... Bxf5 16. Nxc5 bxc5 17. g4 $1 {
This is the key idea for White. White takes control over the very important
e4-square and leaves Black with a passive bishop and no counterplay.}) 16. f4
$14 {This move should be played in order to stop any f5-f4 ideas for Black.
White's idea is to fix the pawn structure and to provoke e5-e4. Then White has
a variety of good plans. First of all, he could undermine the e4-pawn by
playing g3-g4, opening files on the kingside and making the e4-pawn vulnerable.
Another idea is to exchange the dark-squared bishops via d4-square and later
to install his queen on d4 and to block the pawn with a Knight on -e3.
Furthermore, in some positions, White could consider playing Nb5-d4 with the
idea to exploit the week - c6 and e6 squares in Black's camp.} Nxd3 17. Qxd3 e4
18. Qd2 {The mission is completed - the centre is fixed and Black has no
counterplay at all. Very important nuance is that Black's pawn is on c7, not
on c5. Now the d4-square is under White's control.} Qf6 19. Rf2 {This useful
move frees the f1-square for the bishop and overprotects the b2 - pawn.} Bd7
20. Rd1 {White improves his pieces before starting concrete actions.} Qg6 21.
Ne2 Nf6 22. Bd4 Rae8 23. Qe3 {It is important to block e4 - pawn. Sometimes,
Black tries to play e4-e3 and even at a cost of a pawn tries to achieve some
counterplay.} h6 24. Nc3 Rf7 25. Bf1 {The best square for the bishop is e2.
From there it supports g3-g4 and frees g-file for White's rooks.} Kh7 26. Be2
h5 {This is not an attacking move. It is just prophylactic against g3-g4.} 27.
Rg2 Bh6 28. Rf1 Rg8 29. Rff2 Bg7 30. a3 {White shouldn't hurry. He has the
situation under total control and first makes all the useful moves, before
starting any concrete actions.} h4 $6 {Desperation! Black can't stand being
without counterplay and starts playing on the kingside, but this only helps
White.} 31. gxh4 Qh6 32. Rg5 Qxh4 33. Rfg2 {White's rooks are perfectly placed
on the g-file. Now Bxf6 followed by Rh5 is a threat.} Be8 {Black has no other
way to cover the h5-square.} 34. Rxf5 Bh6 35. Rfg5 $1 {Nice resource in
already winning position.} Bxg5 36. fxg5 Nh5 37. Bxh5 Qxh5 38. Qxe4+ Rg6 39.
Qxe8 (39. Rg4 $1 {This simple move, is winning on the spot.}) 39... Rxg5 40.
Qh8+ Kg6 41. Qg8+ Kf5 42. Qc8+ Kf4 {It looks like Black has some counter play,
but Botvinnik with accurate play didn't give his opponent any chance to
survive.} 43. Qe6 $1 Rxg2+ 44. Kxg2 Qf3+ 45. Kg1 {Unfortunately for Black, he
has nothing more than few checks} Qg3+ 46. Kf1 Qf3+ 47. Bf2 Qh5 48. Ne2+ Kg5
49. h4+ {A really nice game by Botvinnik which was used like an example for
White for generations.} 1-0

