1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d6 3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 Bg4 6. Be2 Nfd7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Rc1
e5 9. d5 a5 10. O-O Bxf3 11. Bxf3 f5 12. Be2 Na6 {What to do now? There are 3
options : to play f2-f3, to stay or to take on f5. The important factor in
this position is that the pawn is not on c5. Also, I want to point out that
Black's light-squared bishop is missing. So, entering our familiar structure
by playing exf5 followed by f2-f4 is the right decision.} 13. exf5 $1 gxf5 14.
f4 Kh8 {Black realizes that after e5-e4 his position will be very passive and
tries to avoid it.} 15. Kh1 {Useful move. The king is much safe here.} Nac5 16.
Qd2 a4 17. g3 $5 {Interesting move. White is ready to answer exf4 with gxf4,
opening the g-file and covering the f4-square.} Qf6 18. Qc2 {This move looks
like a loss of tempo, but it makes a lot of sense after a5-a4. Now, the
a4-pawn is hanging and Black can't activate his rook. Moreover, from teh
c2-square, White's queen puts additional pressure on the f5-pawn.} e4 {The
structure is fixed. White is clearly better. There are 2 possible plans. To
transfer the Knight to the weakened e6-square or to block the e4-pawn with a
knight and later to open either the queenside or the kingside.} 19. Rfd1 Nb8 {
Interesting idea. Black is planning Nb8-a6-b4-d3.} 20. Bd4 Qh6 21. Nb5 {
The Knight is going to d4-square} Nba6 22. Qc3 {The point of White's idea. The
queen covers b4 square.} Rae8 23. Re1 {e4-pawn should be blocked and I decided
to do this with the rook.} Re7 24. Bf1 Kg8 25. Re3 Bf6 26. Rd1 Rg7 27. b4 $1 {
White opens the queenside, Black's knight will be kicked from the nice
c5-square.} axb3 28. axb3 Nd7 29. b4 {It is obvious that White is much better,
but now it is time for decisive actions. I decided to transfer my Knight to
e6-square.} Qg6 30. Be2 h5 31. Bxf6 Nxf6 32. Nd4 Rd7 33. Ne6 Re8 34. Ra1 {
This is a multi-purpose move. It is a prophylactic against 34...Ng4 35.Bxg4
Qxg4 and then my rook would have been hanging on d1. Also, it also occupies
the a-file and puts additional pressure on the a6-knight.} Kh7 35. Kg1 $5 {
My idea was to transfer the king to b3 - square and then to open the kingside
with h3-g4.} Kh6 36. Kh1 {I decided that transferring the king with all major
pieces on the board could be dangerous in time trouble and found a new plan.
Transfer the knight to e3-square and then open the queenside. Since the
position is not forced, losing a tempo is not a significant factor. I still
believe that Kf2-e1-d2-c2-b3 was also winning.} Rde7 37. Nd4 Rd8 {Black has no
active plan, he should just wait passively.} 38. Bd1 {Diagram [#] Preparing
Nc2-Re1-Ne3.} Rc8 39. Re1 Rg8 40. Nc2 Qg7 ({If} 40... h4 41. Ne3 $1 hxg3 42.
Rg1 Nh5 43. Ra2 {And it is Black who is under attack.}) 41. Ne3 {Unfortunately,
there was no additional time after move 40 and at this point, I and my
opponent were short on time, which explains some mistakes later.} Kg6 42. c5 $5
Nd7 43. Qxg7+ $6 {Unfortunately, I didn't notice that I can avoid the exchange
of the queens.} (43. Qb3 $1 {With queens on the board Black's position is just
hopeless} dxc5 (43... Qxa1 $2 {is not working} 44. Bxh5+ Kxh5 45. Rxa1 $18) 44.
Bxh5+ $1 {Nice tactical shot.} Kxh5 45. Nxf5 Qf7 46. Nxe7 Qxe7 47. d6 Qf8 48.
dxc7 $18 {Black's position is just collapsing. White has too many threats such
as 49.Qd5+ or 49. Qd1+}) 43... Rexg7 44. c6 Nb6 45. cxb7 Nxb4 46. Ba4 {I saw
this position in my calculation and evaluated it as a winning for White, but
it is not so easy at all.} Rb8 47. Bc6 Rgg8 48. Reb1 Nd3 49. Ra7 {White is
preparing to double on the a-file.} h4 50. Rba1 hxg3 51. hxg3 Nc5 52. Ra8 $2 {
this move simply blunders a pawn.} (52. Kg2 {The simple activation of the king
should have been enough. Black is paralyzed and White can do whatever he wants.
}) 52... Nxb7 53. R8a7 {I was frustrated and decided to keep 4 rooks on the
board hoping to play for a win anyway.} Nc5 54. Rxc7 Kf6 55. Raa7 Rbf8 56. Kh2
Nc8 57. Ra8 Rh8+ 58. Kg2 Rfg8 59. Bb5 Ne7 60. Rxg8 $2 {Unbelievable mistake!
My only excuse is that I had only 30 seconds left on the clock.} (60. Raa7 $1
Rg7 61. Rxc5 {This is the move that I didn't evaluate properly.} dxc5 62. Ra6+
Kf7 63. d6 {and Black can simply resign.}) 60... Rxg8 61. g4 {As you know, one
mistake never comes alone.} (61. Be2 {just keeps the position equal.}) 61...
fxg4 62. Kg3 Rg7 63. Bd7 $4 {The final mistake.} Nxd7 64. Rxd7 Nf5+ $18 {
White can resign here.} 65. Nxf5 Rxd7 66. Kxg4 Rd8 67. Ne3 Rg8+ 68. Kh3 Rg1 {
Nice game, with an unfortunate for me result. At least this becomes a perfect
example to illustrate White's idea in this structure.} 0-1

