{At this classical encounter, we achieve our position of interest at move 20.
White played 20.f4 and fixed the pawn structure achieving the same structure
as in the game of Botvinnik. The significant difference here is that Black's
c-pawn is on the c5-square. This makes White's task much harder because White
does not have the important d4 - square under his control.} 20. f4 Bf6 21. Be3
{White is threatening to take on e5 and also freeing f2-square for his knight.}
Bg7 22. Qd2 {Again, White is threatening to take on e5 and h6} e4 23. Nf2 Nf6
24. h3 Qe8 {With this multi-purpose move, Black is preparing b7-b5 and is
ready to transfer the queen on the kingside via g6.} 25. Kh2 h5 {Stopping g3-g4
} 26. Rg1 Nc7 $1 {Black is ready to open the queenside with b7-b5} 27. a4 {
White is forced to close the queenside. After that, there is no real chance to
penetrate Black's position. The only chance is g3-g4, but Black easily stops
this threat.} Qg6 28. Rg2 Rf7 29. Rh1 Bf8 30. Kg1 Rg7 {Both sides are
maneuvering, White is preparing to play g3-g4, Black is preparing to meet it.}
31. Kf1 Re8 32. Rhg1 Qh7 33. Qd1 Na6 34. Na2 Kf7 35. Ke1 Be7 {Black's next
move is Reg8 and it is obvious that White never can play g3-g4 without losing
material so the draw was agreed.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "Candidates Tournament"]
