[EventRounds "13"]
[EventCountry "URS"]

{In this position, White decides to take on f5. As we already mentioned, this
move is a mistake when Black can answer it with Nxf5!.} 12. exf5 $2 Nxf5 $1 {
White has e4-square under his control, but Black controls the d4 which levels
the game. This particular position looks better for Black, because of the
g3-pawn which weakens White's kingside.} 13. Nge4 a5 $1 {Nice move which ruins
White's structure.} 14. b5 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Nd4 {This position is a perfect
example of the character of the position. White has a full control of the
e4-square, while controls the d4 - square. Now, both sides will start to
consolidate their positions. Black's play looks easier to me: Bf5, Qd7,
doubling the rooks on the f - file.} 16. f3 Bf5 17. Bd3 Qd7 18. Be3 Rae8 19.
Rf2 Re7 20. Rb1 b6 21. Kh1 Bxe4 $5 {Black decides to simplify the position.} (
21... Ref7 $5 {Black can keep the tension.}) 22. Bxe4 Nf5 23. Qd2 Ref7 24. Rbf1
Nxe3 25. Qxe3 Qh3 {The position is absolutely equal, because none of the sides
can break on the queenside. White's bishop looks active on e4, but not
attacking anything. Black's bishop will come on h6-c1 diagonal.} 26. Kg1 Bh6
27. Qd3 Bg5 28. Re2 Kg7 29. Rff2 Rh8 30. Re1 h5 $2 31. Qf1 $2 {Now it is equal
again.} (31. Bxg6 $1 {This brave move gives White an advantage.}) 31... Qd7 32.
Rg2 Bh6 33. h4 Qh3 34. Qf2 1/2-1/2

