{[%evp 0,59,27,27,27,-14,32,32,32,32,29,30,25,31,58,18,58,46,82,49,53,49,27,22,
17,-21,2,22,27,13,35,30,21,16,47,-36,36,24,118,78,97,84,293,445,442,503,503,
522,521,547,547,286,294,641,641,650,654,651,677,677,29985,29988]} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2.
c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. d4 O-O 6. h3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 8. g3 $1 {This move is
the recent trend in the 7...Nh5 variation. The idea is to stop Nf4, but also
White is preparing Nh4.} f5 9. exf5 $1 {This move needs some explanation.
White is almost forced to give up the centre, f2-f3 is not possible and there
is no good waiting move. Black's centre pawns ("e5" and "f5") look dangerous,
but they are not creating any threats. White's plan is simple: finish the
development, castling long and push g3-g4.} gxf5 10. Nh4 {The key idea. Now
Black's knight needs to go back and White's knight on "h4" puts pressure on f5.
} Nf6 11. Qc2 (11. Bd3 $1 {I believe this is stronger.}) 11... e4 $6 (11... Na6
$1 {is better}) 12. Be3 {After "e5-e4" Black central pawns lost their
flexibility. The other drawback of "e5-e4" is that now Black's knight has a
wonderful square at "f4"} Nfd7 13. Ng2 Ne5 14. O-O-O Nbd7 15. Be2 Nc5 16. Nf4
Bd7 17. g4 {The triumph of White's strategy} fxg4 $6 {this move loses
immediately, but it is hard to suggest anything better for Black} 18. hxg4 Nxg4
19. Bxg4 Bxg4 20. Rdg1 {Simple chess, with "h" and "g" files, open it is not a
surprise that Black's king is in great danger.} Nd3+ 21. Nxd3 exd3 22. Qxd3 h5
23. Rxg4 {Eliminating the last defender of Black's king} hxg4 24. Qh7+ Kf7 25.
Ne4 Rh8 26. Qf5+ Kg8 27. Rxh8+ (27. Qe6+ $1 {is mate in 14 according to
Stockfish, but my move also wins}) 27... Bxh8 28. Qg6+ Bg7 29. Bg5 Qc8 30. Be7
{The last suttletie} 1-0

