{[%evp 0,81,27,27,27,-16,32,32,31,31,31,31,31,31,53,18,41,32,56,37,26,37,34,14,
35,37,50,68,95,25,84,21,46,46,22,30,28,28,22,20,23,25,25,30,30,28,47,55,36,46,
76,39,43,66,66,70,78,6,25,54,69,100,100,109,118,108,130,157,147,204,215,212,
207,179,294,298,271,286,279,287,284,286,288,266]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
4. e4 d6 5. h3 O-O 6. Nf3 e5 7. d5 Nh5 8. Be3 {at that time the move 7...Nh5
was very popular and I tried different approaches against it.} Na6 9. a3 f5 10.
b4 {The point of White's setup. White is trying to restrict the knight on a6
and is not reacting to Black's activity on the kingside.} Nf6 11. Rc1 $1 {
even now, White can allow fxe4} h6 (11... f4 $6 {is a strategical mistake.
With no tension in the centre, White has a free hand to start his play on the
queenside.}) 12. Qb3 Kh7 13. Be2 c5 14. b5 Nb8 15. g4 fxg4 $6 (15... f4 16. Bd2
{I believe that White is better here. The plan is to evacuate the king and to
try to open the kingside at the appropriate moment. White has a huge space
advantage and it is not easy for Black to find good squares for his pieces})
16. hxg4 Nxg4 17. Ng5+ Kg8 18. Bxg4 Bxg4 19. Ne6 Qf6 (19... Bxe6 20. dxe6 {
[%cal Rc3d5] If you are wondering what the evaluation of this position is, you
can ask the knight on b8.}) 20. Nxf8 Qxf8 21. Kd2 {Making space for the "c1"
rook} Nd7 22. Rcg1 Bf3 (22... Nf6) 23. Rh3 g5 24. Qb1 g4 25. Rxf3 {I believe
that this was a good practical decision. All White's pieces are more active
and the position is strategically winning} Qxf3 26. Rg3 Qf7 27. Rxg4 Kh7 28.
Ne2 Rg8 29. Qh1 {The rest is simple technique} Nf6 30. Rh4 Qg6 31. Ng3 Bf8 32.
Nf5 h5 33. Kd3 Rh8 34. Rh3 a6 35. Rg3 Qf7 36. Bg5 Rg8 37. Bxf6 Rxg3+ 38. fxg3
Qxf6 39. Qxh5+ Kg8 40. bxa6 bxa6 41. g4 1-0

