1. c4 g6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. d5 {Petrosian
Variation. White is closing the centre without waiting for Nc6. Now the plans
are quite different from the classical variation.} a5 {typical move for this
structure} 8. Bg5 {The main point of White's plan. White is trying to stop
"f7-f5"} h6 9. Bh4 Na6 {This is the mainline. Black's knight is very well
placed on "a6". From here, he controls "c5" and "b4" squares and protects "c7"}
10. Nd2 Bd7 11. O-O Qe8 {another important idea for Black. He needs to prepare
f7-f5, but first needs to break the pin.} (11... g5 {is a strategical mistake
because it weakens the light squares too much.}) 12. b3 {this move also needs
some explanation. White's main idea is to advance his queenside pawns via
a3-b4.} ({but if} 12. a3 $2 a4 $1 {closes the queenside.}) 12... Nh7 13. f3 {
freeing "f2" square for the bishop} h5 (13... f5 {is also possible, but I want
to illustrate you another idea.}) 14. a3 Bh6 $1 {that is the point of Black's
previous move.} 15. Rb1 Nc5 $5 (15... Be3+ {transfering the bishop to the
queenside is also possible and was successfully tried by GM Amin} 16. Kh1 Bc5
17. Qc1 f5 18. exf5 gxf5 19. f4 $14 {0-1 (48) Materia,M (2281)-Amin,B (2690)
Europe Echecs INT 2020}) 16. Qc2 f5 17. b4 {Finally, White manages to push his
queenside pawns.} axb4 18. axb4 Na4 19. Nd1 g5 20. Bf2 g4 21. fxg4 Bxd2 $2 {
Ding misplayed the position here. This move is a strategical mistake} (21...
hxg4 $1 22. exf5 Bxf5 $13) 22. Qxd2 f4 23. gxh5 $18 {Black doesn't have enough
compensation for the sacrificing material and Giri won 40 moves later} 1-0

